<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Agrees on Privatization in Principle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin today said he does not oppose privatizing state enterprises
if it is the only way to protect France's national interests.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Le Monde, Jospin said he would
not in principle reject the disengagement of the state from public
enterprises to become a "minority stock holder."
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the public listing of state
enterprises' stocks will be guided "by industrial strategy" and
not "in the name of an ideological priority."
</P>
<P>
The government, the Socialist premier said, will only maintain
public enterprises which "exercise its activity with a mission of
public service in a non-competitive field."
</P>
<P>
In some industries, "it could be absolutely indispensable to
establish powerful groups by renewing alliances (with other
European groups)," he noted.
</P>
<P>
France is seeking to build pan-European defense and aeronautics
groups with private German and British groups to compete with
dominant U.S. groups.
</P>
<P>
The public listing of stocks of state enterprises, such as the
defense electronics giant Thompson CSF and the aerospace group
Aerospatiale, is expected.
</P>
<P>
Like most continental European countries, France has maintained
state control over railway and city transport and energy
industries.
</P>
<P>
The government has lately opened part of the telecommunication
market by selling 20 percent stocks of the state monopoly France
Telecom.
</P>
<P>
In his latest statement, Jospin also mentioned air transport
services as a possible area for privatization.
</P>
<P>
But a dispute over whether to privatize Air France between the
government and the company's management led to the recent
resignation of Christian Blanc, president of the national
carrier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
