<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Central Bank Raises Fears about Rate Hikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell today to
its lowest level against the German mark in more than two months
as the German central bank president Hans Tietmeyer fanned
speculations that the bank might raise German interest rates in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of insurers in the western German city of
Wiesbaden, Tietmeyer said it is "theoretically possible" that
Germany might raise key interest rates ahead of May next year when
the European Union is due to make the decision on which countries
would be able to join the planned single currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
After his remarks the dollar sank to 1.7645 marks at Monday's
fixing in Frankfurt, compared with 1.7829 marks on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Money traders said that Tietmeyer had unleashed additional
pressure on the markets which had already been alerted by the
announcement of the German Federal Statistics Office on Monday
that Germany's wholesale prices increased sharply by 3.3 percent
in August after a 2.0 percent increase in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
