<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Business Economists See Stable Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. economy is likely to
grow at an average quarterly rate of 2.4 percent over the next
four quarters, a survey by the U.S. National Association For
Business Economics (NABE) said today.
</P>
<P>
Forty-three professional economic forecasters of the NABE
predicted that the U.S. output of goods and services will rise 3.4
percent this year, reflecting the sizzling 4.9 percent rate of the
January-March quarter, and 2.3 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
The results of the latest poll were released at the
organization's annual meeting in New Orleans today and made
available in the U.S. capital.
</P>
<P>
The business economists also predicted that inflation will
remain tame, rising just 2.2 percent this year and 2.8 percent in
1998. The U.S. Consumer Price Index rose 3.2 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
They also expect to see an interest rate increase to insure
against an acceleration of inflation late this year although top
economic forecasters are confident the economy will not exceed the
speed limit set by the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed).
</P>
<P>
Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan told the U.S. Congress earlier this
Summer that the U.S. economy's performance was "exceptional," with
low unemployment and low inflation. He said the central bank
expected growth to range between 3 percent and 3.25 percent this
year and between 2 percent and 2.5 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is predicting rises of 3.5 percent
in 1997 and 2 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congressional Budget Office also sees 3.4 percent
growth this year and 2.1 percent next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
