<HEADLINE>   France Reduces Public Deficit by Billions in One Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- France's public deficit was
down to 258.8 billion francs (about 43 billion U.S. dollars) by
the end of July, 13.8 billion francs (2.3 billion dollars) less
than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the public deficit was only 202.3 billion francs (33.6
billion dollars) by the end of June, said the French Ministry of
Finance, which did not explain why the deficit rose by 50 billion
francs in July.
</P>
<P>
State income increased by 2.7 percent last month as compared to
July 1996, more than the 2.6 percent increase predicted by the
1997 budget law passed under the former right-wing government.
</P>
<P>
The newly imposed 15 percent corporate tax increase had brought
the state 82.6 billion francs (12.1 billion dollars) more of state
income by June as compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
This year's state expenditure by the end of July increased to
950.8 billion francs (158 billion dollars), a 0.5 percent rise
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Ordinary spendings in civil and military fields decreased by
1.8 percent and 3.7 percent, while investments in both fields fell
by 13.1 percent and 8.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
