<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel to Enhance PCs with Video Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corp. the world's
leading semiconductor maker, is stepping up efforts to get home
personal-computer users hooked on video.
</P>
<P>
The company announced today that the product, called the Create
and Share Camera Pack, is an easy-to-use, all-in-one PC
communications, photo and video editing package that plugs into
Pentium processor-based high-performance PCs. At a price of a few
hundred U.S. dollars, the package includes a video camera and
image-processing hardware that can be used as a video phone. It
also offers a variety of software for sending images over the
Internet or turning snapshots into greeting cards or calendars.
</P>
<P>
Though hardly a new concept, Intel's move exemplifies its
determination to promote new uses of personal computers that
require powerful chips, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Intel began selling video-phone products in 1994, and consumers
have generally found them to be too expensive and too poor in
visual quality. For one thing, video uses more data than can be
easily fed through a typical phone line. Because of delays and
compression techniques, images often looked jerky, cartoon-like
and blurry.
</P>
<P>
Faster computers, using chips such as Intel's Pentium MMX and
Pentium II microprocessors, are now better at compressing and
playing video images, according to experts of the company.
</P>
<P>
A company manager predicted that sales of video phone cameras
will triple to 1 million this year, and sales of software and
hardware will grow to 10 million U.S. dollars by 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
