<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Asks Israel to Step Up Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- France today asked Israel to
"go further" in making peace with the Palestinians, and the
Israeli army to "proceed significant redeployments" in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
"We encourage the Israeli government to go further, to present
other concrete measures and then give back the form to the peace
process," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques
Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman appealed to Israeli authorities to impose a
complete freeze on Jewish housing projects in Arab lands, stop
seizing Arab lands and destroying the Arabs' houses, stop
confiscating identity cards of Palestinians, and stop other
"unilateral acts" which could twist the results of the final talks
on the status of the Palestinian autonomous territories.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided Sunday to lift step by step its blockade of the
Palestinian territories, give back some tax fund to Palestinians
and veto a new housing project in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"These small steps should be followed up by the relaunch of a
real peace process which needs to be dynamic, needs a vision for
the future, a confidence established that we appeal from our
heart," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He was echoing an earlier comment by French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine on Radio Europe 1 today, in which the minister said
the Israeli decisions made Sunday were "small steps" and that his
severe criticism of Israel last Friday was an "appeal from his
heart."
</P>
<P>
In an unprecedented attack upon Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu last Friday, Vedrine accused Israel of adopting a
"catastrophic policy" toward Palestinians, which had driven the
latter to the "unprecedented level of exasperation and despair."
</P>
<P>
"The status quo is not defensible. One should go out of the
present vicious circle which gives terrorism the right of veto to
the peace process," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Palestinian authorities to fight terrorism,
but stressed that Israel should take "necessary measures to
appease tension."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman praised U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright for her peace mission in the Middle East last week, and
said that France and its European partners are willing to join the
U.S. efforts and to help implement all intermediary peace
agreements between Israel and Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
