<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Razali Calls for Real Efforts for UN Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Razali Ismail,
President of the 51st General Assembly of the United Nations,
today called on member states to unite and make real efforts for
the on-going reforms and strengthening of the world body.
</P>
<P>
In a closing address, Razali said that U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's reform package put forward in mid-July "deserves our
full and expeditious attention without being casualty to
politics."
</P>
<P>
"The task of strengthening the UN will depend in large part on
the UN's ability to adapt to change, beyond creeping incremental
adjustments," he noted.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that the UN "will not be strengthened if reform
only concentrate on cost-effectiveness, efficiency and better
coordination," adding that such objectives alone would divert
attention from the UN's real functions and Charter
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
"If the UN is to survive, it has to transform itself from an
organization serving only the interests of states to one serving
the interests of peoples living in an interdependent and global
society," Razali pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The 51st session of the UN General Assembly will close after
its final meeting on Monday. The 52nd annual session is going to
open on Tuesday with its focus on overhauling the UN machinery.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who came to office on January 1, 1997, has since been
making reform efforts to enable the world body to better confront
the challenges of the new millenium.
</P>
<P>
"I would hope that the leaders will come to the Assembly
convinced that the most important issue before them is reform,"
the Secretary-General told a recent press conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
