<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Primary Teachers to Be Retrained over Literacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- All of Britain's primary
school teachers will be retrained by local authority instructors
in order to grasp government methods for teaching reading and
writing, according to a government report today.
</P>
<P>
The report, the Implementation of the National Literacy
Strategy, by the government's Literacy Task Force said that
standards of teaching were "unacceptably haphazard" and that
failed teaching methods lay at the heart of children's literacy
problems.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, which will be overseen by 200 new
government-funded literacy consultants, all primary school
teachers will receive several days training over the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it is reported that nearly 40,000 primary school
headteachers and governors are to be given intensive management
training next year to implement and monitor the drive to improve
literacy standards.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Byers, the school standards minister, heralded the
measures as "a practical agenda for action". However, teacher
unions are sceptical about government claims that these measures
will help raise standards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
