<HEADLINE> Razali Criticizes Blind Unilateralism in UN Dues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The President of the
51st session of the United Nations General Assembly, Razali
Ismail, Monday criticized "blind unilateralism" in paying the dues
to the world body.
</P>
<P>
"Blind unilateralism will be the undoing of the UN," Razali
warned in a closing address to the 51st session.
</P>
<P>
He said that the 51st session had made remarkable achievements
in advancing the purposes and principles of the U.N. Charter and
reforming the organization.
</P>
<P>
"The most disappointing and perhaps the most crucial piece of
unfinished business of the 51st session is the continuing
stalemate over the issue of payment of arrears and of restoring
fiscal stability to the organization," the President pinted out.
</P>
<P>
He said that financial crippling of the U.N. continued to
obstruct the momentum for reform.
</P>
<P>
"Arguments about complicated legislative procedures, attaching
arbitrary conditions to payments and using the media to cast a
different version do not reduce what is simple a solemn treaty
obligation," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats and observers believed that Razali was implying
the United States for its tough conditions to the payments of its
arrears reportedly more than 1.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A reduction in U.S. dues is one of the conditions the
Republican-controlled U.S. Congress has set for paying the
arrears.
</P>
<P>
But most other U.N. members, including Washington's allies,
resent the placing of any conditions on payments they say the
United States is treaty-bound to make. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
