<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kidnapped WFP Aid Worker Released in Somali </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The abduction of Idiris
Mohamed Osman, an aid worker from the World Food Program (WFP) in
the Somali capital ended peacefully Sunday night after the
intervention of community elders and officials from WFP.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Salah Garad Omar, a Somali official from the WFP who
was flown from Nairobi for the release efforts, said with the
help of the elders, the abduction of Osman ended without the
payment of any kind of ransom.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about those who kidnapped Osman, Garad blamed
militiamen loyal to the local non-governmental organization
(NGO), Green Hope, for being behind the abduction.
</P>
<P>
According to Garad, Osman was abducted so as to settle
differences among the Green Hope officials who maintained a
relationship with WFP.
</P>
<P>
"They thought Osman could solve their problem in that way," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Osman, who was kidnapped three days ago in South Mogadishu,
looked healthy but humbly dressed with a scarf round his neck,
and said he was treated fairly well.
</P>
<P>
Speaking briefly to the press at the WFP office in South
Mogadishu this morning, Osman said despite the deprived freedom,
he was fed well and faced no torture in the house near K-4 of
South Mogadishu where he was kept out of sight.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his agency's latest activities, Osman said WFP
was supplying dry food to the famine and drought stricken regions
of Bay, Bakol and Lower Jubba, where convoys of dry food rations
were distributed to the poor.
</P>
<P>
The agency has also been paying for work rations to teachers
and voluntary health workers in the Somali capital.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the faction led by Hussein Mohamed Aidid who
controls south Mogadishu, has also condemned the abduction of
Osman, warning that no more such activities will be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has had no effective government since president
Mohamed Siad Barre was toppled in 1991, and the Horn of African
country is divided between a range of armed factions.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Qanyare Afrah, interior secretary for Hussein Aidid,
said today that they have arranged new strong forces to combat
the crimes being committed in the streets of Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
