<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barclays Evolves New Unit Trust Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) - Barclays bank is evolving a new
strategy for its 6 billion pounds (8 billion US dollars) unit
trust business, according to an announcement by the bank here
today.
</P>
<P>
On September 29, the bank will retitle its unit trust operation
Barclays Funds Limited and introduce its new management.
</P>
<P>
The unit trust industry is overrun by product proliferation
and, from September 29, Barclays Funds Limited is introducing a
new simplified fund range called Barclays Investment Portfolios to
be available through Barclays branches and the Bank's own
salesforce.
</P>
<P>
The range will include an income fund, a fund of funds focused
on Growth and a balanced fund of funds for income and growth.
</P>
<P>
The bank was previously committed to selling its funds through
its 1,200 branches and is the biggest unit trust manager among the
high-street clearers.
</P>
<P>
The move confirms the growing role of IFAs - independent
salesmen typically working for commission - in distributing the
products of financial services companies.
</P>
<P>
The UK's 22,000 IFAs have boosted their share of sales of both
unit trusts and life and pensions policies in recent year.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Time said: "Their success has confounded
widespread predictions that many would be forced out of business
by competition from banks, such as Barclays." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
