<HEADLINE> Canada Wants Permanent Fishing Rules Monitoring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada wants to create a
permanent high-seas enforcement program designed to conserve
Atlantic fish stocks, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
This will top Canada's agenda this week at a meeting of an
international fishing organization.
</P>
<P>
Canada hopes a permanent agreement will be in place to ensure
there are observers on every fishing vessel and satellite tracking
of a percentage of fleets to prevent overfishing, said the
Department of Fisheries and Oceans.
</P>
<P>
Other issues to be decided at the week-long meeting include
establishing quotas for the 12 fish stocks that are found beyond
Canada's 200-nautical-mile limit, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Fisheries Organization (NAFO) members
carried out a two-year pilot project after the turbot war between
Canada and the EU in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Since the project began, the number of infractions detected by
Canadian inspectors has decreased by over two-thirds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
