<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Urges U.S. to Revive Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
six Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states concluded their two-day
meeting today, calling on the United States to play its leading
role in putting the Middle East peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
In their final communique issued after the 64th ministerial
meeting, concluded in southern Saudi resort city of Abha, the
foreign ministers said they followed up with concern the
deadlocked Middle East peace process and the deterioration of
living conditions in the occupied Arab territories, according to
reports from Abha by Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates
(UAE), Oman, Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the ministers made it clear to the
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright whom they met Sunday
before starting the meeting that they hope the U.S. help push the
peace process back to its normal track.
</P>
<P>
They said the GCC's continued support to the peace process
was conditional to the Israeli government's commitment to the
agreements it signed with the Arab states.
</P>
<P>
They called on Israel to remain committed to the
land-for-peace principle, U.N. resolutions and withdrawal from the
occupied Syrian Golan Heights and south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Regarding GCC's relations with Iran, the communique said that
the ministers discussed the Gulf-Iranian ties and hoped that the
coming phase would witness confidence building measures for
realizing regional security and stability.
</P>
<P>
It said the GCC countries underlined its unwavering stance to
forge good ties with Iran that hinge on good neighborly ties,
mutual respect and non-interference in internal affairs of other
states.
</P>
<P>
The ministers referred in particular to the "positive
statements" of the new Iranian President Mohammad Khatami who
said that his country would open a new page in relations with the
Gulf states.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministers underlined in the communique their
support to the UAE' sovereignty over the three Islands of Abu
Musa, Greater and Lesser Tunbs which are currently occupied by
Iran.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also called on Iraq to implement all U.N. Security
Council resolutions related to its 1990 aggression of
Kuwait. "This is the only way for lifting the sanctions imposed
by the Security Council on Iraq," they said.
</P>
<P>
As to the U.N.-Iraq oil-for-food deal which allows Iraq to sell
2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months to purchase
medicine and food for the Iraqi people suffering under the U.N.
sanctions, the ministers welcomed the U.N. speedy approval for the
second six months in June.
</P>
<P>
They also underscored the need to safeguard Iraq's
independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
On their internal process to the unification of customs
tariffs, the ministers expressed content with the steps already
taken by the Products Classification Committee which has so far
finalized the classification of almost 94.5 percent of the listed
products needed for the final stage of unification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
