<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Praises Albright's Visit as Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat said today that U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright's commitment to the peace process will
help move it forward.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the statement after a "very significant and
positive" meeting with President Hosni Mubarak in Egypt's
Mediterranean city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he and Mubarak assessed the results of Albright's
first tour in the region since she took office early this year and
all other issues related to the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Albright's visit created a new fact that is more positive than
the previous period," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Albright had clearly adhered to all principles
adopted by the Madrid peace conference including the "land for
peace" principle as well as U.N. resolutions 242 and 338.
</P>
<P>
The top American diplomat urged Israel to refrain from taking
unilateral actions, namely confiscation of Arab lands, expansion
of Jewish settlements, demolition of Palestinian houses and
withholding of tax revenues, said the PNA leader.
</P>
<P>
"She also underlined the U.S. government's commitment to the
peace process and the Oslo agreements," he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright visited the Palestinian self-rule area and Egypt
during her multi-leg trip to the Mideast that began on September
10.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arafat criticized the Israeli government for
obstructing the peace process and refusing to implement the
agreements it signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He urged the international community to safeguard the outcome
of the Palestinian-Israeli agreement on Palestinian self-rule in
the interim period signed in Washington in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"It is vital that Israel faithfully implements the
Palestinian-Israeli agreements signed under the American and
European guardianship," he added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he informed Mubarak of the situation in the
Palestinian self-rule areas under the Israeli punitive measures
imposed in the wake of a series of suicide bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Also present at today's meeting were Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa, Mubarak's political adviser Osama el-Baz, Secretary
General of the Palestine Liberation Organization Executive
Committee Mahmoud Abbas, PNA Local Government Minister Saeb
Erekat, Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil
Sha'ath.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on today's meeting between Arafat and Mubarak, PNA
Minister of Higher Education Hanan Ashrawi said it will help come
up with a unified Arab discourse in the face of future
developments in the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi threw cold water on the agreed meeting between
Palestinian and Israeli officials in Washington, which is seen as
a "minor step" achieved by Albright's shuttle diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
"The coming Washington talks will be dedicated to finding means
to resume peace talks without actually delving into vital issues
in the negotiations themselves," she said.
</P>
<P>
Now that Albright proved unable to make any changes in the
Israeli mentality, Ashrawi cautioned, the causes of crisis in the
Mideast region continue to exist.
</P>
<P>
Albright announced last Friday that senior advisors of Arafat
and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu will meet in
Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this month, Arafat's assistant Abbas will hold
talks in New York with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy on
means to move forward the Mideast peace march.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks stalled in March over a new
Jewish settlement project in traditional Arab East Jerusalem,
which the Palestinians want as their future capital. The string of
suicide bombings in Jerusalem since end of July has fueled the
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
