<HEADLINE> Inflation Drops in Botswana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Botswana has witnessed
a decline in its inflation rate for three successive months and
the lowest increase in the cost of living index for almost eight
years, the country's Central Statistics Office reported today.
</P>
<P>
Year-on-year inflation has dropped from 8.9 percent in July to
8.5 percent in August, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Index for the cost of living rose by only 0.2 percent, the
lowest monthly increase since November 1989.
</P>
<P>
At the end of August, the index stood at 106.8 percent, up
from 106.6 in July. The base is 100 as in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
The small increase in the cost of living index is attributed
to price reductions in petrol and diesel.
</P>
<P>
The petrol price dropped by eight Thebe (about two cents) per
liter and diesel by four Thebe (about one cent). These changes
have resulted in a drop in the fuel and power sub-index by 1.1
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
