<HEADLINE> Iraq to Grant Entry Visas to 93 Iranians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has decided to allow 93
Iranian citizens living in the United States to come to visit
Shiite Muslim holy shrines in Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Tourism Authority has authorized the granting of
entry visas to 93 Iranian passport holders, INA said.
</P>
<P>
They are the first batch of overseas Iranians permitted to
enter Iraq for pilgrimage under an instruction by Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Shiites and Sunnis are the two major factions of Islam. Iran is
the only Shiite-dominated country in the region but the most
important Shiite shrines are in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq fought an eight-year war from 1980-88 and are
still at odds with each other.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government has recently decided to allow Iranian
expatriates to visit Iraq through the Qadesia checkpoint on the
Iraqi-Jordanian border and El-walid checkpoint on the Iraqi-Syrian
border.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a Baghdad invitation for Iranian pilgrims to visit
holy shrines in Iraq was brushed off by Tehran, which insisted
that negotiations be conducted first to make proper arrangements.
</P>
