<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Cypriot Leaders to Discuss Security: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- President Glafcos Clerides
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash will meet soon to
discuss security issues, a top U.S. official announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State, Madeleine Albright was quoted by
Cyprus News Agency as speaking at Larnaca Airport, where she was
on a quick stop-over from Lebanon on her way back to Washington,
that both Clerides and Denktash have informed the U.S. of "their
willingness to meet soon to discuss security issues".
</P>
<P>
Albright described the development as "a substantial step",
that would help reduce tension and improve the overall atmosphere
for serious negotiations to tackle the core issues of the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
"Today's agreement represents a significant step in the right
direction," Albright said, adding that it "symbolizes the same
spirit to settle differences peacefully and not through the
threat of force", citing as a similar example the agreement
reached between the leaderships of Greece and Turkey in Madrid
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
She reaffirmed the commitment of President Bill clinton to
a resolution of the Cyprus problem, citing the appointment of
Richard Holbrooke as Presidential envoy for Cyprus as "concrete
manifestation of the American commitment to use all resources
at our disposal to help the people of Cyprus".
</P>
<P>
The date of the Clerides-Denktash meeting has not been set
yet, according to the U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the U.S. looks forward to the further reduction
of tensions through the talks that herself, Ambassador Holbrooke,
Assistant Secretary Marc Grossman and U.S. special coordinator for
Cyprus Thomas Miller, will be consulting next week in New York
with officials from the region.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Coordinator Miller also left here this evening after a
four-day visit to the island during which he discussed the
Cyprus problem with President Clerides and Denktash. He also had
meetings with U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus, Gustave
Feissel and other foreign diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Miller's tour in the region, which also took him to
Ankara and Athens, was aimed at making preparations for a
visit to the region by U.S. Presidential Emissary for Cyprus
Holbrooke, scheduled for November.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when
the island was divided after Turkey sent troops and took
over the northern third in the wake of a failed coup seeking
union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
