<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several EU Members Insist on Institutional Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Several member states of the
European Union (EU), including France, here today insisted on the
necessity of an institutional reform of the EU before its planned
eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
"There should be absolutely an institutional reform before the
expansion," French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said at a
council meeting of the 15 EU foreign ministers held in Brussels
Monday.
</P>
<P>
He added that France did not want to see an enlarged Europe
which however could not function normally.
</P>
<P>
At the Amsterdam EU summit held last June, the leaders of the
15 EU member nations failed to reach an accord on the EU's
institutional reform but decided to postpone the issue until the
first wave of eastward expansion which could happen at the latest
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
France, Italy and Belgium demanded a rapid institutional reform
in a declaration issued at the meeting Monday. The declaration
will be submitted to the other member states on the occasion of
the signature on October 2 in Amsterdam of the adopted treaty at
the Amsterdam summit in June.
</P>
<P>
The three countries note in the declaration that the Amsterdam
treaty did not respond to the necessity of "substantial progress"
regarding the reinforcement of the EU institutions.
</P>
<P>
They also said in the declaration that "such a reinforcement is
an indispensable condition of the conclusion of the first round of
accession talks" scheduled to start at the beginning of next year.
</P>
<P>
The declaration, if it is only signed by the three countries,
will be annexed to the Amsterdam Treaty. Austria and Luxembourg,
which are for the EU's institutional reform, are also expected to
sign the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The reform of the European institutions will deal with the
redefinition of the composition of the European Commission and the
extension of vote to qualified majority on sensitive subjects like
justice and internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Germany is reportedly opposed to the reform, particularly on
the extension of vote to qualified majority on issues such as
immigration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highest Inflation Hits Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The highest inflation rate
since 1993/94 financial year has hit Uganda due to drought which
has caused country-wide famine and a rise in food prices,
reported local daily "The Monitor" today.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's inflation which had been contained at single-digit
level for a long period of time, shot to a high of 11.8 percent
in May this year and was recorded at 10.1 percent by June before
it slightly dropped to 9.6 percent and 8.9 percent for July and
August respectively.
</P>
<P>
The above position, described as the worst in two years by a
senior economist at the Ministry of Finance last week, doubled
the inflation level recorded during the same period in the
1995/96 financial year.
</P>
<P>
The end of June 1993/94 financial year saw inflation at 16.1
percent, while a low of 3.4 percent was recorded for June 1995
and 5.4 percent for June 1996.
</P>
<P>
The economist said, "The current 8.9 inflation rate isn't
something to smile about" as the targeted and acceptable
inflation level for the economy should be at 5 percent a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
