<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-15 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Expresses Opposition over Settlers' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today expressed his opposition to Jewish
settlers' move into an Arab neighborhood in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The settlers' move was not good for Israel, Netanyahu said at
a news conference. His remark came after 15 settlers moved into
two houses in Ras Amud, a mostly Arab neighborhood, Sunday night.
Their presence sparked a violent Palestinian protest.
</P>
<P>
"We believe what is happening in Ras Amud is not good for
Jerusalem, not good for the state of Israel," Netanyahu said,
adding that all policies relating to the Jerusalem issue should
be guided by the government instead of by private initiatives.
</P>
<P>
He said while he respected the property rights of
individuals, the Ras Amud issue was very sensitive and should be
dealt with by the government only. "We think, on sensitive
issues, we should be the ones who are making decisions," he
claimed.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu failed to announce what actions the government
would take against the three settler families. He said he could
only act within the law, implying he might seek legal means to
handle this thorny issue.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai expressed surprise
over the settlers' motives by moving into Ras Amud. Appearing
before the Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense
Committee, he said the latest incident could be exploited by
those who wanted to ignite the already tense situation.
</P>
<P>
A heavy presence of Israeli police in the Ras Amud was
deployed to prevent possible outbreak of widespread Palestinian
protests and violence. Still, some Palestinian youths threw
stones at the buildings housing the 15 Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority's (PNA) Minister for Jerusalem
Affairs Faisal Husseini, who visited the site this morning,
demanded the Israeli government act to remove the settlers. He
warned about the explosion of the situation if the settlers
remain living in the mostly Arab neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
"I believe there will be a decision, but not to take now and
this moment," he said, implying that the Palestinians could
choose violence to counter the provocation by Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli opposition leaders tightened their pressure
on the government to remove the settlers from Ras Amud.
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Ehud Barak said that if he were the prime
minister, he would have consulted with security and judicial
officials to find a proper way to evict the settlers. He warned
that the new settlement would create a serious danger to the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid held Netanyahu responsible for the
incident, echoing the media reports that Netanyahu knew about
the settlers' plan before they moved into Ras Amud. He added
that he was waiting for a strong reaction from the United States
to oppose the settlers' action.
</P>
<P>
The settlers took the action after a committee of the Interior
Ministry cleared the last legal barrier for a go-ahead of the Ras
Amud housing project, in which U.S. millionaire developer Irving
Moscowitz plans to build 70 housing units for the Jews.
</P>
<P>
In the light of the current tension between Israel and the
PNA, the Israeli government is expected to halt the Ras Amud
project at the stage. Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein has
been asked to study the legal possibility of blocking the
project by invoking state security and public order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
