<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Benefits From IMF's Debt-Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique will benefit
from a debt-relief initiative of the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), the country's Finance Minister
Tomas Salomao said today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement over the debt-relief issue was a result of
Mozambique's commitment to meet three conditions to be eligible
under the world's highly-indebted poor countries.
</P>
<P>
The criteria were that Mozambique was defined as a poor
country and its foreign debt of nearly six billion U.S. Dollars
was unmanageable, said Salomao.
</P>
<P>
The third condition was good performance shown by President
Joaquim Chissano's administration to introduce and implement
structural adjustment programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
The most visible results of these efforts were a sharp decline
in the inflation rate and an impressive stability of the
Mozambican currency, the Metical, Salomao said.
</P>
<P>
Creditors had recognized Mozambique's debt burden was a severe
obstacle to the development of the southern African nation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, debt payments take up about one-third of the
country's revenue, while debt service runs at 30 percent of its
yearly export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is carrying out a major reconstruction plan
following 17 years of civil war, which killed at least one
million people and destroyed basic infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
