<HEADLINE> EU Foreign Ministers Discuss Expansion Name List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the
15 EU (European Union) member states here today discussed the name
list of the countries which could be invited to talks on the EU's
first wave of eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that the ministers met to have in-depth
talks on the Agenda 2000 policy blueprint unveiled in July by the
EU's executive body, the European Commission, which picked up only
half of the 10 eastern European applicants as suitable countries
to participate in the accession talks scheduled for early 1998.
</P>
<P>
The five countries, Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary,
Slovenia and Estonia, are expected to join Cyprus in for talks for
the EU's most ambitious expansion yet.
</P>
<P>
The five others -- Latvia, Lithuania, Slovakia, Romania and
Bulgaria -- were deemed as inadequate in their preparations for EU
membership.
</P>
<P>
Voicing concerns about creating a new curtain between east and
west, Sweden, Denmark and Italy, favor opening talks with the 10
countries at the same time. But a final decision waits to be made
until an EU summit in Luxembourg in December.
</P>
<P>
EU sources were quoted as saying that foreign ministers were
also likely to condemn Belarus for failing to launch political
reforms and to suspend EU participation in talks between the
government of President Aleksander Lukashenko and his opponents.
</P>
