<HEADLINE> U.S. Pressured to Keep Troops in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States was
pressured today to agree to keep its troops in Bosnia beyond next
July in order to guarantee the fragile peace process in the
ethnically-split country.
</P>
<P>
Both Britain and Denmark indicated at a council meeting of EU
foreign ministers held Monday in Brussels that they would like the
U.S. to extend its military presence in Bosnia following the first
post-war municipal elections there at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has reportedly promised the U.S.
Congress to withdraw the NATO-led stabilization force (SFOR) from
the multi-ethnic country next Summer.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said that it would be very
difficult for international forces to leave next year when asked
whether he would support such a move by the United States.
</P>
<P>
But he also said that Britain would only stay on in Bosnia if
the U.S. remained, too. "We need the U.S. presence for our
presence to be safe," Mr. Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Danish Foreign Minister Niels Helveg Peterson, the current
chairman of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE), said he favored extending the military presence of
the U.S. in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that Denmark intended to be involved
"continuously" if there were an extended international presence in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He added that without the presence of SFOR, composed by around
37,000 soldiers, the municipal elections would not have been
feasible.
</P>
<P>
Robert Frowick, head of the Bosnia mission of the OSCE,
reportedly said Sunday in Sarajevo that it was totally essential
to have an international military presence in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Cook expressed the hope Monday that the words of Mr.
Frowick as an American would "carry weight in Washington". France
has also earlier made clear that it would not stay if the U.S.
troops left Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
