past five years, he said, stressing that Athens intended to expand
its ties with Georgia, especially in the trade sector.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Shevardnaze said that his talks with Greek
leaders had focused on sectors which held promise for future
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He spoke specifically of the telecommunications and transport
sectors, as well as possibilities of cooperation in ship-building,
farming and banking.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnaze, who arrived here today for a three-day official
visit to Greece, had also held talks with his Greek counterpart
Costis Stephanopoulos today.
</P>
