<HEADLINE> Paris Establishes Card Index on Jewish Properties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The French capital Paris has
been authorized to establish a card index on all the real estate
properties robbed from Jews during the Vichy collaboration period
of early 1940s, Paris Mayor Jean Tiberi said today.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin has signed a decree allowing Paris
to set up the index which is aimed at "verifying the origins of
property and possible robbing that the owners of the properties
could have been subjected to," said Tiberi.
</P>
<P>
The decree only covers the Paris area of Prefecture of Seine
where many Jews were robbed of their properties and sent to
Germany to get killed during World War II.
</P>
<P>
A state advisor Noel Chahid Nourai, who is president of the
Council of Patrimony Charged with the Inventory and Filing of
1,389 apartments in the Paris region, had advised the creation of
the card index.
</P>
<P>
The Paris Municipality was accused last year by journalist
Brigitte Vital-Durand of maintaining many flats which were
originally robbed from Jews during World War II, especially in the
Medieval Marais district of Paris where many Jews live.
</P>
<P>
At the demand of Tiberi, Nourai set up a commission of experts
consisting of representative members of the Jewish community, the
members of the association of former deportees who survived German
concentration camps, historians, jurists, and representatives of
state institutions.
</P>
<P>
According to the French law, the establishment of a card index
on properties of an ethnic minority in France needs the approval
of the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Crack Down on Fraud in Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton Monday ordered an immediate moratorium on new home health
care providers to allow new regulations to be implemented and to
prevent "fly-by-night providers" from abusing Medicare.
</P>
<P>
In a speech before the Service Employees International Union,
Clinton detailed efforts to put fraudulent providers of
home-health care out of Medicare -- the nation's health care for
the elderly. Currently, Medicare enrolls up to 100 new home health
care agencies a year, the fastest growing part of the system.
</P>
<P>
"First we're going to keep scam and ripoff artists from getting
into the Medicare system in the first place," Clinton said. "These
kind of practices amount to a fraud tax on all the taxpayers of
the country. For those of you who work in health care, they cost
public confidence in the work that you do."
</P>
<P>
During the moratorium, Medicare will enlist no new home-health
care providers, Clinton said. Federal regulators will develop
tougher rules designed to weed out dishonest providers, such as
requiring that they post surety bonds of at least 50,000 dollars,
have a minimum number of patients before enrolling Medicare
patients and submit detailed information on all of the businesses
they own.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time Medicare has halted new home health care
providers. The program spends 18 billion dollars a year on home
health care, up from 2.5 billion dollars just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA)
will re-enroll home-health care agencies every three years.
Independent audits will be part of that re-enrollment process, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
HCFA will also double the number of audits of home-health care
agencies and increase the number of claims reviews by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a report to Congress last July, government auditors told
Congress that 14 cents of every dollar spent by Medicare was lost
to instances of fraud, abuse or simple error. Home-health care
agencies accounted for 16 percent of overpayments, the report
found.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
