<HEADLINE> UNICEF Warns of Looming Humanitarian Crisis in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) today warned that a humanitarian crisis is imminent
in Sierra Leone unless steps are taken to combat malnutrition and
diseases in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
Tony Bloomberg, UNICEF's representative in Sierra Leone, was
quoted by the press as saying in London that regional embargo on
the country should be lifted to allow supplies to be shipped in
from neighboring Guinea or Liberia.
</P>
<P>
"We feel we need a proper cross-border operation to prevent a
humanitarian crisis. What we want to avoid is malnutrition and
lots of dying children," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS)
formally approved sanctions and blockade on Sierra Leone on
August 30 to force out the military government led by Major
Johnny Kromah, which seized power from elected President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah in a coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
As it has been mandated to enforce the embargo, the west
African peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG last week bombed a
vessel docked in the Freetown port.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG accused the vessel of bringing in arms and ammunition,
but Sierra Leonean authority insisted that there was only rice on
board.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone is reported to suffer one of the highest rates of
infant mortality in the world and the situation is believed to
have steadily deteriorated since the coup.
</P>
<P>
Bloomberg said the country's overall malnutrition level for
children is approaching 10 percent while malaria, measles and
acute respiratory infections are also on the increase.
</P>
<P>
"The 10 percent malnutrition level is a warning sign -- we
need to give people supplementary feeds but there isn't enough in
the country," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
