<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debris of Missing German, U.S. Army Planes Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Aircraft debris have been found
some 250 kilometers off the Namibian coast two days after a German
and a U.S. military planes went missing in the area over the South
Atlantic, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
German media quoted Namibian air traffic control authorities as
saying on Monday that a Namibian ship had spotted about 20 pieces
of debris, including half a aircraft seat, a piece of a cabin door
and German papers, 255 kilometers northwest of Walvis Bay in
Namibia.
</P>
<P>
The German Defence Ministry today also said that a large pool
of oil had been discovered in a nearby area which could be the
crash site of the German aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The German army plane, a Tupolev 154 with 24 people on board,
and a U.S. C-141 transport plane with nine crew members and
passengers went missing at the same time in the South Atlantic
area late Saturday. It was feared that they might have collided in
mid-air.
</P>
<P>
German Defence Ministry spokesman Hans-Dieter Wichter confirmed
that neither of the two missing military planes had been equipped
with collision warning systems. The TU-154 also did not have a
black box to record flight data.
</P>
<P>
The air traffic control authorities of Namibia said Monday that
they had not been informed of the exact landing time and flight
route of the German plane which was due to make a stopover in the
Namibian capital city of Windhoek en route to Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
German navy officials, however, noted that the German plane's
flight plan had already been approved by all relevant authorities.
</P>
<P>
A huge air and see rescue operations are currently underway to
search for wreckage and possible survivors. However, until Monday
evening no survivors or bodies had been found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
