<HEADLINE> Pregnant Zambian Students Allowed to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Girls who have been expelled
from schools or colleges in Zambia this year for being pregnant
will be allowed to take the exams to continue their study,
Education Minister Syamukayumbu Syamujaye said here today.
</P>
<P>
Those girls who wish to continue their study after delivering
their babies will allowed to do so, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks while opening the national symposium on
girls' education and taking to national scale of the Program for
the Advancement of Girls Education (PAGE).
</P>
<P>
Syamujaye said the government has taken deliberate affirmative
action in favor of girls and that from this year selections to
grades 8 and 10 will be on an equal basis and will no longer be
in favor of boys.
</P>
<P>
At university level from this year, 25 percent of the state
bursars will go to female students while the remaining 75 percent
will be competed for equally by both female and male students, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"At the level of administration, I want to see more females in
positions of leadership and decision making in the Ministry of
Education," the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
"This is important as we can only succeed in the
implementation of our policies in the education of girl-child if
women are represented at all decision making levels," he said.
</P>
<P>
A few weeks ago, according to Syamujaye, three women were
appointed deputy permanent secretaries at his ministry.
</P>
<P>
He urged the symposium to address the strong misconception
that a woman's place is in the kitchen and that a woman should be
subservient to man as this largely influences the decision when
it comes to girls' education prospects.
</P>
<P>
Expansion of the PAGE program to national scale has been made
possible by the Norwegian government which contributed three
million U.S. Dollars to the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
