<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Premiers Agree to Hold National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Nine of Canada's provincial
premiers has agreed to a framework for public consultations on
national unity, local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
After an 11-hour negotiation behind closed doors in Calgary on
Sunday, the premiers came out with guidelines to govern public
consultations, which will initiate this fall and try to wrap up by
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The consultation will result in resolutions, which each
provincial legislature can then pass as a goodwill gesture before
a Quebec election, expected as early as next Spring.
</P>
<P>
The premier said the process may eventually lead to
constitutional reform.
</P>
<P>
Yet, they stressed that this can't be accomplished until there
is a federalist government in the French-speaking province of
Quebec.
</P>
<P>
Quebec's separatist Premier Lucien Bouchard did not attend the
meeting, which was supposed to last two days but wrapped up in
one.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines recognize Quebec's "unique character", but
insist that all provinces and citizens are equal in Canada.
</P>
<P>
"In Canada's federal system, where respect for diversity and
equality underlies unity, the unique character of Quebec society,
including its French-speaking majority, its culture and its
tradition of civil law, is fundamental to the well-being of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
"Consequently, the legislature and government of Quebec have a
role to protect and develop the unique character of Quebec society
within Canada," the guidelines said.
</P>
<P>
The premier also agreed to a first ministers conference in
November or December on non-constitutional issues such as social
policy, health care and youth employment.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien praised the premiers
today for renewing a call to recognize Quebec's unique
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to congratulate them for their responsible
leadership," Chretien told reporters today.
</P>
<P>
However, the Quebec government dismissed the initiative as less
than the province was offered in the failed Meech Lake and
Charlottetown constitutional accords.
</P>
<P>
"They are even burying the concept of distinct society. Now
they only talk about a vague 'unique character of Quebec'," said
Jacques Brassard, Quebec minister of intergovernmental affairs.
</P>
<P>
The proposals don't satisfy any of Quebec's traditional
demands, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
