<HEADLINE> Nigerian Varsity Stages New Conduct Code for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Authorities of the Lagos State
University (LASU) have rolled out a new code of conduct for
students, banning consumption and use of all alcoholic beverage
and liquor on campus.
</P>
<P>
According to the new LASU code of conduct, any student caught
using or consuming alcoholic beverages or liquor would be
dismissed from the university.
</P>
<P>
A statement containing the code of conduct said the university
authorities would resist any interference on matters of
discipline from whatever quarter.
</P>
<P>
The new rules also re-stated the ban of all secret cults and
confraternities, saying that any student found to be a member,
sponsor or patron of such organizations would be summarily
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
"The possession, carrying or use of arms and dangerous weapons
by students on the campus is, henceforth, banned if any student
found to possess, carry or use such weapons shall be dismissed,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"All students' religious activities, including drumming and
singing, should be restricted to the chapel or Mosque area," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The rules and regulations come at a time of renewed cult
violence at the neighboring University of Lagos, where two
students lost their livers two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Institutions of higher learning in Nigeria have become hotbeds
of cult-related violence since the early 1990s, and authorities
have vowed to curb trend, but with little or no results, the News
Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
LASU, established in 1984 with a student intake of 300, now
has 15,000 students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
