<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eleven Million Go Hungry Annually in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- As many as 11 million
Americans go hungry every year, of which two million suffer sever
hunger, according to an Agricultural Department study being
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
The study defined hunger as not having enough food. Severe
hunger would be when children in the household experience physical
feelings of hunger.
</P>
<P>
The figure did not include an estimated 600,000 homeless
people, according to the study obtained by USA Today.
</P>
<P>
The study is being released as the Agriculture Department
convenes a summit to discuss how to save some of the 96 billion
pounds of food wasted every year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government is reining in the growth of the 22
billion-a-year food stamp program. The move could increase the
ranks of the hungry.
</P>
<P>
Of the nation's 100 million households, about 88 percent have
enough quality food, another eight percent sometimes cannot afford
to eat healthful food, and four percent go hungry at some point
during the year, the report says.
</P>
<P>
The most serious form of hunger, in which children as well as
adults don't have enough to eat, is experienced by about 800,000
households or two million people.
</P>
<P>
The report found hunger is more common in households headed by
women, those with young children, among blacks and Hispanics and
in cities.
</P>
<P>
Today's summit is expected to discuss how to save excess food
for the poor. They are targeting restaurants, hotels,
manufacturers and retail stores that throw food away when it is no
longer fresh enough to sell or when they prepare more than they
need.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
