<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Rich Members Hope to Share Bill More Fairly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
rich members today complained that their contribution to the EU
budget was too heavy and they held out hope that the bill would be
shared more fairly.
</P>
<P>
"Correcting the distribution of contributions to the Union's
budget is an essential part of the future of the EU budget,"
Swedish Foreign minister Lena Hjelm-Wallen said at a meeting of EU
foreign ministers held Monday in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
voiced the same view to his counterparts at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Under the historic Agenda 2000 blueprint unveiled in July by
the European Commission, the EU's executive body, the ceiling of
EU members' contributions would stay at 1.27 percent of gross
domestic product between 2000 and 2006.
</P>
<P>
However, Spain and Portugal indicated at the meeting that it
was far from enough. Spanish Foreign Minister Abel Matutes even
said that he did not intend to lose a cent for his country in the
EU's most ambitious eastward expansion yet scheduled for early
next century.
</P>
<P>
"It is not the moment to make threats, but it's clear the
Spanish government would not accept that enlargement is to the
detriment of the southern countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
British sources said that London would stick to its own rebate
from the EU budget, which was hard won by former Conservative
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
But southern countries, including Spain, Portugal and Greece,
are not expected to give up EU funds used to help the economic and
agricultural sectors of their poorer regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
