<HEADLINE> Cypriot President to Talk with Denktash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- President Glafcos Clerides
will enter a U.S.-proposed dialogue with Turkish Cypriot Leader
Rauf Denktash on security issues, Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides said here today.
</P>
<P>
"President Clerides today accepted the proposal by U.S. special
coordinator for Cyprus, Thomas Miller, to start a dialogue with
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, in Nicosia, under the
auspices of U.N. resident representative Gustave Feissel,"
Kasoulides said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
The two are to discuss all issues concerning security, without
any pre-conditions or a set agenda, Kasoulides added.
</P>
<P>
"It was proposed that all issues mentioned in recent U.N.
resolution on Cyprus that concern armed forces, armaments and
measures to reduce tension along the demarcation line, should as a
first step be discussed within the framework of a program for the
complete demilitarization of Cyprus," Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that Clerides will enter the dialogue
with "a constructive spirit and willingness to promote the
aforesaid goals."
</P>
<P>
The proposed Clerides-Denktash meeting was first announced
earlier today by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright who
stopped over in Cyprus on her way back to Washington after a trip
to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Observers here described the proposed meeting as a positive
step toward a Cyprus settlement after the failure of two rounds of
direct talks between the leaders of the two communities in July
and August.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when
Turkish troops landed on the east Mediterranean island and took
over the northern third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the island as a bi-communal, bi-zonal
federation through peace talks, but no tangible results have so
far been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
