<HEADLINE> More Gold Mine Closures Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The world's gold producers
will have to close more mines and some companies may go out of
business because of the weak gold price, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Canada's gold giant Barrick Gold Corp. said it was
closing half of its 10 mines because of the low gold price.
</P>
<P>
Barrick becomes the first major gold producer to announce mine
closings, and other companies will have to follow suit, according
to today's Globe and Mail newspaper here.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 22 percent of the world's gold mines have
operating costs above the current gold price of around 324 U.S.
dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
If the price of gold drops closer to 300 dollars an ounce,
nearly one-third of the world's mines will not be economical, the
paper quoted industry consultant Gold Fields Mineral Services Ltd.
of London as saying.
</P>
<P>
Here in Canada, Bob Buchan, chief executive officer of Kinross
Gold Corp. of Toronto, believes the industry has hit bottom.
</P>
<P>
Yet, he also expects more mine closures and some companies to
go out of business altogether.
</P>
<P>
On world markets, the gold price has dropped 18 percent over
the last year, largely because of selling by central banks that no
longer view bullion as a critical part of their monetary strategy.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, central banks sold 220 tons of
gold, compared with 72 tons in the same period last year,
according to Gold Fields.
</P>
<P>
The only glimmer of hope for producers is the record demand for
gold for jewelry-making in several Middle Eastern countries and
India.
</P>
<P>
But that demand won't solve the problem of the central banks,
which still have a huge supply of gold and could keep the market
depressed for years, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0057 </DOCNO>
