<HEADLINE> US Grounds Stealth Fighters After Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States grounded
its stealth fighters today after one of the craft crashed during
an air show in Maryland Sunday and investigations started on the
losses of three military aircraft over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
An Air Force F-117A "Nighthawk" crashed on the skirts of
Baltimore Sunday; a Navy F-A-18 Hornet crashed in Oman and its
pilot was killed; and an Air Force C-141 transport is presumed
lost after a potential mid-air collision with a German military
plane off the coast of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Searching was underway for the nine crewmen aboard the U.S.
C-141 Starlifter cargo plane, which was returning to Ascension
Island from Namibia. No wreckage or survivors have been found.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech F-117 crashed during an air show at Middle River,
Maryland, setting two houses on fire and injuring six people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 49th Fighter Wing in New Mexico, home base for
all 53 F-117A fighters, suspended routine flights as a
precautionary measure through today.
</P>
<P>
The Navy is investigating the crash of the F-A-18 during a
routine training mission about 75 miles (126 km) northeast of the
southern Omani port of Raysut.
</P>
<P>
The plane had been operating from the aircraft carrier USS John
F. Kennedy, whose home port is Mayport, Florida. 
</P>
