<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wage Gap Expands Between US Men, Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- After nearly two decades
of a narrowing wage gap between men and women in the U.S., it's
now widening again, The New York Times Reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that labor statistics show median weekly
earnings for full-time working women in the country are just under
75 percent of the men's median, down from 77 percent four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Some labor economists have suggested that the gender gap may
have something to do with welfare reform unleashing a flood of
unskilled women on the job market.
</P>
<P>
Other analysts say it is more likely that the numbers reflect
changes in the makeup of the workforce, overall economic trends,
or statistical flukes, than any real reversal of women's workplace
status.
</P>
<P>
But many people warn that it is far too soon to say with any
certainty just what, if anything, the earnings data predict.
</P>
<P>
From 1979 to 1993, U.S. women's median earnings rose from 62
percent of men's to 77 percent. And in the early 1990s, the
narrowing gap was widely trumpeted as evidence of women's greater
opportunities, greater education, and greater work experience --
trends that were predicted to continue indefinitely, edging women
ever closer to pay equity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
