<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Okays Third Annual Loan for Bolivia Under ESAF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today announced the approval of the third annual loan
for Bolivia in an amount of about 46 million U.S. dollars under
the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF).
</P>
<P>
The IMF also agreed on an extension of the loan's period
through September 1998 in a bid to support the government's
economic and reform program for 1997 and 1998. The loan will be
disbursed in two equal semiannual installments, the first of which
is available immediately.
</P>
<P>
The economic program for 1997 is designed to reduce inflation
to 7 percent and achieve a GDP growth of 5 percent. There is
likely to be a widening of the external current account deficit to
7.5 percent of GDP in 1997 from 5.1 percent in 1996 due to imports
of intermediate and capital goods rise significantly owing to
investment by capitalized enterprises and the construction of a
gas pipeline to Brazil. Excluding these imports, the deficit would
remain at 2.4 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The ESAF is a concessional IMF facility for assisting member
countries that are undertaking economic reform programs to
strengthen their balance of payment and improve their growth
prospects. The loans carry an interest rate of 0.5 percent and are
repayable over 10 years, with a 5.5 year grace period.
</P>
<P>
Bolivia joined the IMF in December 1945. Its quota is about 171
million dollars equivalent and its outstanding use of IMF credit
currently totals about 239 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
