<HEADLINE> Mozambican Police Destroy Illegal Firearms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican police has
uncovered and destroyed nearly 12,000 illegal firearms since
1995, a police source said today.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Raul Frela said nearly 8,000 hand grenades
and about 14,000 land mines were uncovered and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more than 8,000 ammunition clips, 378 boxes of
assorted munitions and more than 124,000 rounds of loose
ammunition were also destroyed.
</P>
<P>
An unspecified quantity of explosives, military communication
radios and other materials were also uncovered, Frela noted.
</P>
<P>
Most of the weapons were found in the central province of
Zambezia, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican and South African police were reportedly
cooperating to dismantle arms hidden during 17 years of civil
war. The hostilities ended with the signing of a peace accord
between the government and the former rebel movement Renamo in
Italy in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
