<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Antwerp Stages International Jewelry Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Below-par economic
performance has left its imprint on the 15th international jewelry
trade fair which was being held at Antwerp.
</P>
<P>
Yet exhibition manager Karen Renders today told reporters that
though the size of the annual event shrank as far as the number of
exhibitors was concerned, the three-day show could be described as
grown in the sense of the quantity of quality products.
</P>
<P>
A total of 135 exhibitors showcased their products on 7,500
square meters of floor space. Most exhibitors were from the
Benelux, or Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg. But precious
stone carvers and diamond cutters also came from Germany, Italy,
France, Cyprus and as far as from Japan.
</P>
<P>
Renders said that the trade fair was expected to grow in future
as the list of participating countries expanded to include
countries on other continents which are key jewelry designers and
manufacturers, such as Sri Lanka which is an Asian country rich in
precious stones.
</P>
<P>
Exhibition goers, mostly professionals in the trade, spotted
out a couple of new trends, some still in the bud and others in
full resurrection.
</P>
<P>
Color stones, especially bigger ones, are being used more and
more in jewelry making and decoration. So is platinum, or white
gold, the use of which, like stainless steel, is on the rise
again.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition stand was devoted specially to medal titanium
which has so far been closely linked with aerospace industry for
its extremely light weight and extraordinary strength.
</P>
<P>
Apart from rings, ear-rings and bracelets, titanium is also
used to make ear-ring pins for its 100-percent anti-allergy
characteristic.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas Delaide, who won the Jewel Award '97 today, told the
press that visitors were fascinated by artistic presentations via
indigenous yet creative designs. The Antwerp designer won the
trophy last year as well.
</P>
<P>
The three-day trade fair will end Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
