<HEADLINE> Mozambique Accuses U.S. of Undermining Land Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has accused
the United States of attempting to undermine efforts to draw up
an international treaty banning anti-personal land-mines.
</P>
<P>
The accusation was made today in the country's capital Maputo
by demonstrators belonging to a group called the Campaign Against
Land-mines outside the U.S embassy, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The group said in a statement that the U.S. government has
abandoned its earlier position to distance itself from
preparations for a ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
It said instead, Washington is proposing a number of
alterations to the draft text at a conference taking place in
Oslo, the Norwegian capital which is aimed at drawing up the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The group fears the alterations will drastically weaken the
treaty, expected to be signed in December in the Canadian capital
of Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is among the countries seriously affected by land
mines planted during the 17 years of civil war, which ended in a
peace accord in October 1992. 
</P>
