<HEADLINE> Peace Talks Start With Unionists' Absence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) - The multi-party peace talks on
Northern Ireland started today in Belfast with the absence of
pro-British unionists from the talks.
</P>
<P>
The first plenary of the peace talks was adjourned shortly
after it started while the chairman of the negotiations, former
U.S. senator George Michell, tried to persuade the unionists to
take part.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) said it would not quit the
talks following the admittance of Sinn Fein, the political wing of
the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
However, UUP leader David Trimble said his party wanted talks
with Mitchell and British government minister Paul Murphy to
discuss "the format of any substantive talks and the handling of
the outstanding procedural issues."
</P>
<P>
Trimble said that his party, which represents 60 percent
Protestant majority that wants to stay British, would attend the
talks "as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
The UUP's absence from today's talks was prompted by an IRA
statement last week which said the guerrillas could not endorse
ground rules drawn up by Mitchell on voting rights and the
disarming of guerrilla groups during the talks.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Ireland issued a joint statement early today to
persuade the unionists into joining the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
