<HEADLINE> Monarchy to Remain in Canada for Now: Chretien </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien said today that he has enough on his plate and doesn't
want to be dragged into the monarchy debate now.
</P>
<P>
Chretien has been asked to clarify his stand on the issue
whether the country should cut its ties with the British monarchy.
</P>
<P>
"I have enough with the separatists of Quebec. I don't want to
have problems with the monarchists of Canada at this time," he
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
John Aimers, head of the Monarchy League of Canada, wrote to
Chretien, demanding that he be known on whose behalf Industry
Minister John Manley was speaking when he called for an end to the
British queen's role in Canadian affairs.
</P>
<P>
Chretien is also asked to clarify his own position on the
monarchy.
</P>
<P>
Minister Manley told a Vancouver newspaper last week that it is
probably time for Canadians to say good-bye to the British
monarchy.
</P>
<P>
Chretien said that Manley is a "very candid" man and, like
other ministers, has some freedom to express his views.
</P>
<P>
To abolish the monarchy in Canada, it would need the consensus
of all the provinces and the House of Commons, Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
Following Chretien's response, Aimers said that while he
accepts Chretien's position, the prime minister should have given
a positive affirmation of support of the British monarchy.
</P>
</TEXT>
