<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. European Car Sales Reach 9.4m So Far This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- New car sales in western
Europe rose by 3.1 percent to reach 9.37 million in the first
eight months of this year, according to figures released today by
the European Automobile Manufacturers' Association.
</P>
<P>
The figures were higher than expected and prompted
manufacturers to raise their 2.3 percent forecasts for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The association said that sales in Italy jumped by 35 percent
in the first eight months and almost 44 percent in August alone as
the Italian government introduced an incentive program in January.
</P>
<P>
Sales in Spain also remained buoyant due to the changes in
vehicle excise taxes, with a rise of almost 12 percent so far this
year and a year-on-year increase of 17.6 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
Strong UK sales also boosted the European total. The main
reason for the country's 6.3 percent sales rise in the first eight
months was the introduction of the new registration prefix last
month.
</P>
<P>
However, sales on the French market were not so buoyant, with a
fall of 22.1 percent in the year to August and a drop of more than
29 percent last month, undermined by the termination of the
government's incentive program last September.
</P>
<P>
The Volkswagen group continued to dominate western Europe's
market, with General Motors overtaking Fiat to regain second place
overall among manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japanese and South Korean car makers continued to
gain ground, with their sales both increased by more than 10
percent, more than three times the increase in the total market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
