<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key to Socialist Legal State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- It is of vital importance for
the government organs to exercise power in accordance with the
laws in the process of building China into a socialist legal
state, a delegate said here today.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Xiaoyang, a delegate
to the ongoing 15th National Party Congress, told Xinhua that
only when the government departments and officials perform their
duties in accordance with laws, can they expect people to
abide by laws in their life and work.
</P>
<P>
Qiao, deputy director of the Commission of the Legislative
Affairs of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress (NPC), said that the powers of the government departments
are given by the people and, therefore, the powers could only be
used to serve the people.
</P>
<P>
"Governing by law, in my views, means that power is decided by
law and not by the enforcer. The exercise of power, thus far,
should be decided by the legal procedures and not by the
enforcer's will," Qiao said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin pointed out in his report to the opening session of
the congress that "the smooth progress of the undertakings of the
Party and the state invitably requires that there must be laws to
go by, that the laws must be observed and strictly enforced, and
that law-breakers must be prosecuted."
</P>
<P>
Qiao held that the above-mentioned principles have been
advocated for 18 years and the principle of "there must be laws to
go by" has been better observed.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, NPC and its Standing Committee,
China's highest law-making body, have promulgated 321 laws and
regulations since China began reforms and opening-up, and 119 of
them were put into effect after the 14th National Party Congress
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the State Council, the country's highest governing
body, has issued 770 sets of regulations in the past 18 years.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to 5,000-odd regulations formulated by
governments, which are empowered to do so, and 30,000 regulations
and rules issued by the central ministries, a socialist legal
system with the Constitution as the cornerstone has taken shape,"
Qiao said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that problems still exist in the "laws must be
observed and strictly enforced." The biggest obstacle for the
building of a socialist legal state is "some do not perform their
duties according to the law."
</P>
<P>
One of the reasons for this is that the law-making and law
enforcing departments in the past paid little attention to how to
enforce the power, which is the most effective measure to prevent
power abuse.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the unhealthy style of work and local
protectionism are among the others that affect the strict
enforcement of laws. "It is impossible to require the people to
abide by law while the executive departments and their staff do
not observe the laws," Qiao said.
</P>
<P>
According to Qiao, in order to carry out the principle "there
must be laws to go by, the NPC and its Standing Committee in
recent years put equal emphasis on law-making and supervision on
law enforcement and made ten more inspections nationwide on the
execution of dozens of laws.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the current five-yearly Party congress, Jiang
also put forward the new concrete measures in this regard, such as
"instituting a system of responsibility for law enforcement and a
system of assessment and examination."
</P>
<P>
Qiao emphasized that the issue to perform the duties according
to the law should be treated as a political issue which is closely
connected with the credibility of the Party and the state.
</P>
<P>
He said that if a government department does not perform their
duties according to the law, it is just like a person does not
keep his promise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
