<HEADLINE> Public Support for Hashimoto's New Cabinet Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's newly formed cabinet is supported by only 28 percent of
respondents to a Kyodo News Survey, with most objecting to the
appointment of a veteran politician with a conviction for bribery
as a minister.
</P>
<P>
The support rate compared with the 50 percent the previous
cabinet received at its inauguration last November.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone survey conducted Saturday and Sunday covering
1,000 male and female voters nationwide, 59 percent said they do
not support the new cabinet, which as formed in a reshuffle last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
74 percent of the respondents said they thought Koko Sato, a
veteran politician convicted of taking bribes in the 1970s
Lockheed payoff scandal should not have been appointed head of the
Management and Coordination Agency.
</P>
<P>
Of those who backed the new cabinet, 32 percent or the largest
proportion, said they supported the cabinet because there were no
others appropriate for the positions.
</P>
<P>
Of those who disapproved of the new cabinet, 37 percent, the
largest group, said the cabinet has problems in political ethics.
</P>
<P>
Of the respondents, only 27 percent supported the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), while 52 percent said they did not
support any particular party in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
