<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long-Term Heavy Responsibilities - 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Party would lose the
support and confidence of the people if corruption is not
effectively checked, an official of the Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection (CCDI) stressed.
</P>
<P>
Liu Liying, 65, a delegate to the ongoing Party congress,
quoted Jiang Zemin as saying that "the fight against corruption is
a grave political struggle vital to the very existence of the
Party and the state."
</P>
<P>
The CCDI and its subdivisions across the country are Party
organs responsible for investigating Party members' violations of
law, she said.
</P>
<P>
The job of discipline inspection is becoming increasingly
challenging as the economic restructuring in the country deepens,
Li pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In the course of introducing shareholding system, it is
unavoidable that corruption may crop up, she said.
</P>
<P>
Liu was one of the leading judges in bringing Jiang Qing, one
of the members of the "Gang of Four" up for trial in 1980.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, she was one of those in charge of the illegal
fund-raising scandal that involved a total of 3.2 billion yuan.
The case helped provide important clues to the case of former vice
mayor of Beijing Wang Baosen and former Beijing Party secretary
Chen Xitong who was expelled from the Party about a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the characteristics of the cases these years in
which Party members were involved, Liu said that she met greater
difficulties because the cases are becoming increasingly
complicated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improves Democracy, Legal System (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China has made a big stride
in improving socialist democracy since it pursued a policy of
reform and opening to the outside world in the late 1970s,
especially since the 14th Party congress held in 1992.
</P>
<P>
This has laid a solid foundation for building a socialist
country ruled by law, said some law-makers at a press conference
held by the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) here today.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yang, minister of justice, said progress has been made in
developing and legalizing socialist democracy since the start of
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China has worked hard to building a legal system to
guarantee improved legislation, fair judicature, strict
enforcement of laws and extensive publicity of law knowledge among
ordinary people, he said.
</P>
<P>
The country is marching toward the goal that there must be laws
to go by, that the laws must be observed and strictly enforced,
and that law-breakers must be prosecuted, he added.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question on human rights in judicial affairs,
Xiao said that the personality, personal safety, lawful property
and rights to defense, lodging complaints and providing
information against offenders -- rights which have not been
deprived of or restricted according to law -- will not be
infringed upon in China.
</P>
<P>
The Law on Prison Management, approved by the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress, sets strict and
detailed requirements for policemen. Those who violate the law
will be subjected to administrative and judicial punishment, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
