<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lanzhou-Xining-Lhasa Fiber Optic Cable Installed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Installation of a strategic
fiber optic telecommunications line linking the remote Tibet
Autonomous Region with inland provinces has been completed 25 days
ahead of the schedule.
</P>
<P>
The cable, which stretches some 2,739 km in length, links
Lanzhou, capital of Gansu Province with Xining, capital of Qinghai
Province, and Lhasa, capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The line passes through 23 counties, cities and district
featuring difficult geographical, geological and climatic
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Over 20,000 construction workers participated in the
construction of the project, with three deaths resulting from the
difficult conditions.
</P>
<P>
The line, which has a capacity of 21,000 long-distance
telephone lines, will greatly improve telecommunications in
related regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Establishes Project Hope Training Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A "Project Hope" training
base was recently opened in the coastal city of Huludao, northeast
China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The base will train teachers for Project Hope primary schools
and various other staff members working in the project, a national
campaign to help young drop-outs return to school.
</P>
<P>
The base, which will provide courses and lodging for 600
people, covers 5.25 ha and has floor space of over 1,200 square
meters.
</P>
<P>
The complex was constructed by the Liaoning Provincial Office
of "Project Hope." Liaoning has collected over 70 million yuan in
donations for Project Hope since 1992 and has allocated funds to
construct more than 500 schools and helped more than 100,000
drop-outs return to school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
