<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Gives Loan to Philippines, Bangladesh, Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) said today that it has approved three loans worth 183
million U.S. dollars to the Philippines, Bangladesh and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam will get a 50 million dollar concessional loan from the
ADB to improve its lower secondary education, the Manila-based
multilateral financial body said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The loan is interest-free and repayable within 40 years and
carries a service charge of 1 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh will receive a 40 million dollar interest-free loan
to help the government provide its urban poor with an innovative
package of primary health care services.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's Urban Primary Health Care Project, the first in
South Asia, will target the urban poor in four major cities which
have most of the country's slums.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines will obtain 93 million dollars in loan to
upgrade its six airports in the south.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be from the bank's ordinary capital resources and
carries an interest rate to be determined in accordance with the
bank's pool-based variable lending rate system for U.S. dollar
loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
