<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weaker Amid Rate Cut Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
the day weaker against its U.S. counterpart after hitting a
26-month low earlier.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed at 71.74 U.S. cents, further lower
than yesterday's close of 72.28.
</P>
<P>
Ongoing fears of another domestic interest rate cut continued
to place pressure on the local unit.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar hit a low of 71.65 U.S. cents this
morning, its lowest level since it reached 71.42 in mid-July 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The Aussie is continuing to suffer because of speculation
there is going to be another cut to official interest rates,"
senior foreign exchange trader Darrin Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar was at 86.81 from
87.17 against the Japanese yen and at 1.2675 from 1.2826 against
the Deutsche mark.  
</P>
