<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shopping Mall's Offer A Touch of Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Shopping malls in Shanghai,
China's leading metropolis, are attempting to add a touch of
refinement to their thriving business by allocating space to
galleries.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey revealed that galleries can be found in 80
percent of Shanghai's shopping malls, including famous ones such
as First Yaohan, Parksons, and the East Sea Shopping Center,
according to Shanghai-based Business News.
</P>
<P>
Shopping Mall managers note that the addition of galleries has
proved to be mutually beneficial.
</P>
<P>
They point to the fact that major department stores can enhance
both their popularity and business by adding galleries which
attract an increasing number of steady consumers. They also note
that galleries also help to enhance the shopping environment
and polish the image of a mall.
</P>
<P>
Galleries contribute to a certain proportion of profits, which
many estimate placing the level at as high as 25 percent.
Therefore, according to one gallery manager, the interests of all
sides are served by joining to promote sales for the galleries.
</P>
<P>
Chen Citing, manager of the Haiyi Gallery in the East Sea
Shopping Center, plans to sponsor a series of art lectures and
auctions in cooperation with the shopping center in order to
enhance the popularity of his establishment.
</P>
<P>
Stores and galleries attempt to accommodate the tastes of the
majority of consumers by offering decorative paintings belonging
to pop art genre.
</P>
<P>
The first floor of First Yaohan offers decorative paintings
priced from 100 to 800 yuan, with more refined higher price
painting available on the fifth floor for wealthier consumers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
