<HEADLINE> Peace Conference Held in Somalia for Solving Clan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A widely attended peace
conference ended at Harardhere District, in central Somalia on
Monday night, reaching an agreement for settling disputes between
clans.
</P>
<P>
The conference was participated by 700 delegates from the
three clans of Abgal, Murusade and Habar Gidir who all belong to
the large Hawiye community, Mohamed Sheikh Ahmed, one of the four
co-chairmen of the conference, said today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the three-day conference has succeeded in
pacifying the two clans of Abgal and Murusade in the central
regions while the third party, the Habar Gidir clan, was playing
a mediatory role and hosted the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The co-chirpersons said that the conference reached a 10-point
agreement in settling all kinds of disputes from land ownership
quarrels to property restoration squabbles.
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of the conference, the attendants appealed the
other Hawiye communities, including politicians, to reconcile
unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
They also called for the unconditional opening of
Mogadishu's air and seaports, the formation of a representative
administration for the capital and the restoration of the dignity
of the Somali people before the world communities by establishing
a government of national unity in Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
