<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loans to Africa Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The nature of World Bank loans
to Africa has been blamed for huge debt burden on African
countries, The Business Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
A financial consultant was quoted as saying that the World
Bank did not release loans to the benefiting countries on time,
and most of the time, interest would have started accruing on the
loans ahead of the release.
</P>
<P>
"The bank is in a position to lend four billion U.S. Dollars a
year to sub-Saharan Africa, but surprisingly at the end of each
fiscal year, the bank group usually has outstanding millions of
dollars waiting to be disbursed," said Mazi Emmanuel Ivi,
chairman of Target International Ltd.
</P>
<P>
This means "that the commitments are there but the draw-down
is not there," added Ivi, who spoke at a recent IMF/World Bank
pre-yearly general meeting briefing in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
According to him, no African countries, including those that
have completely embraced the structural adjustment program and
those that are yet to do so, have really achieved accelerated and
sustainable economic growth and development.
</P>
<P>
Despite the assurances give by the bank, most African leaders
still believed that Africa "is very uncomfortable with its (World
Bank) policies," because its loans posed a bigger debt burden to
Africa than any of the other highly indebted continents, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
Another investment consultant, Hebert Orji, alleged that loans
approved by World Bank for African countries were being paid into
big banks like Citibank, Manhattan Bank to mention but a few,
while the countries they were meant for did not get to know that
the loans had been disbursed.
</P>
<P>
He said the funds might even be in these banks for a period of
two months generating interest for them as a result of lack of
communication between the World Bank and the benefiting
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's CPI Rises Slowly in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Israel's consumer price
index (CPI) rose a lower-than-expected 0.4 percent to 152.3
points in August, compared with 151.7 points in July, Israeli
Central Statistics Bureau announced today.
</P>
<P>
The index was offset by a seasonal drop in the prices of
clothing and shoes, while its moderate appreciation was
attributed primarily to price increases in food and farm produce.
</P>
<P>
The prices of food and farm produce rose by 1.2 percent and
5.1 percent respectively last month, while those of clothing and
shoes dropped by 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the slow rise of the index is due to the
slowdown in the depreciation of the U.S. dollar, rather than the
decision of the Bank of Israel to raise interest rates last month.
</P>
<P>
"Experience shows that when the dollar depreciates, the index
goes up, and when it appreciates, the index goes down," said
Doron Tsur, head of research at Sahar Securities.
</P>
<P>
"Interest rates go up and down, but we have had a roughly 10
percent rate of inflation for the past four years," he said.
</P>
<P>
After cutting interest rates by 1.2 percent in June, the Bank
of Israel raised the rate by 0.7 percent to 13.4 percent last
month due to inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate in the first eight months of the year ran at
6.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over Half S. African Homes Electrified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Some 54.6 percent of
homes in South Africa have been connected with electricity by the
end of last year, said a report issued recently by the National
Electricity Regulator.
</P>
<P>
"Since 1991, when the electrification drive took off, a total
of two million new connections have been made, " the report said.
</P>
<P>
This has changed the lives of approximately 15 million people,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Following the development of the electricity industry,
electricity consumption grew an average 1.8 percent a year
between 1989 and 1995, with the largest proportion of electricity
being consumed by factories, according to South Africa's Central
Statistical Service (CSS).
</P>
<P>
The CSS census shows that between 1989 and 1995, the growth
rate of electricity consumption by households is four percent a
year, compared with an average 2.1 percent growth rate for the
manufacturing sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Develops New Vaccines for Animal, Human </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at Nigeria's
National Veterinary Research Institute (NVRI) have developed
three new vaccines to check rising bacteria induced animal and
human diseases.
</P>
<P>
The development followed the discovery in the institute's
earlier research that some vaccines produced for some infected
animals were later found to cure chronic diseases in humans,
according to Nvri Abubakar Lamorde.
</P>
<P>
The three vaccines are named black-quarter blaxy and
gasgagerine (BBG), hanta-vac and vomac-b, The Business Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
While the BBG is a three-in-one vaccine used for both cattle
and ruminants, the hanta-vac cures water-borne diseases which
infect animals through the lungs and the vomac-b is an
enterotaemil (a type of diarrhoea) for ruminants, Lamorde said.
</P>
<P>
He said the vaccines were in the final stage of field trials
after which they would be commercially produced.
</P>
<P>
According to Mathias Agba, head of bacteria vaccine
production, human beings contract the diseases after the
consumption of infected cattle or ruminants.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some vaccines earlier developed to cure skin
diseases in animals were used on human beings and found to be
effective, having cured some skin infections suffered for many
years.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the demand for bacteria vaccines is on the
rise and over 16 million doses of them were produced last year in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The demand for vaccines was quite high in spite of
competition from imported vaccines, said Oheari Marcus, head of
viral vaccine production division.
</P>
<P>
Marcus said that poultry vaccines accounted for about 90
percent of the total vaccine output and over 36 million doses of
poultry, dog, cat and cattle viral vaccines were produced in the
last few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
