<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Centenarian Communist Never Gives up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- One of the first members of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) was 104-year-old Tan Tiandu,
who is one of the most valuable witnesses to the Party's
vicissitudes in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
Tan was born in Gaoming County in south China's Guangdong
province, in April, 1893, and took part in the "May 4th Movement"
in 1919 and activities for the establishment of the CPC in the
1920s. He became a founding member of the CPC on July 1, 1921.
</P>
<P>
"Before the Second Congress in 1922, the Party had only 195
members, but the figure has grown to 58 million at the time when
we are holding the 15th National Congress of the Party," the old
man commented.
</P>
<P>
Tan had been arrested four times and imprisoned five by the
Kuomintang before new China was founded in 1949, but he never lost
faith in the Party.
</P>
<P>
Tan's wife Ou Mengjue is also an old communist. They lost their
two children in the old days and he says, "I hope young people,
especially young CPC members, can treasure today's happy life that
was created by revolutionary forerunners, and can carry the
communist cause through to the end."
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that the CPC leadership will grow stronger
generation by generation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
