<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Shelves Government, Private Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
today announced the postponement of some government and private
projects financed by commercial banks in a bid to enforce economic
stability following the rupiah depreciation against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Mar'ie Muhammad said at the parliament that
the projects to be postponed was valued at 38.92 trillion rupiah
(2,900 rupiah equals one U.S. dollar) or 24.1 percent of the
161.78 trillion rupiah projects financed by state-run enterprises
and private firms.
</P>
<P>
The government will also reschedule some projects which are
worth 62.69 trillion rupiah or 38.7 percent of the total projects
planed for the 1997-98 fiscal year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, most of the projects to be postponed
are items in mining, energy, oil and transportation fields as well
as some projects with a high import content.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie said the purpose of the move is to reduce the country's
current account deficit which has reached 9.8 billion U.S. dollars
or 3 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The move is the follow up of the government's reform package
announced on September 3 to prevent the current currency crisis
from plunging into an economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's rupiah, like other regional currencies, has come
under fierce speculative attacks following de factor devaluation
of the Thai baht and the Philippine peso in July. The rupiah has
fallen more than 10 percent in the past month and nearly 25
percent since January this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
