<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Lists Conditions for Aid Supplies to S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The West African Peace-keeping
Force (ECOMOG) carrying out embargo on Sierra Leone has announced
requests for humanitarian supplies to the country.
</P>
<P>
Relief agencies wishing to export humanitarian supplies must
first convince ECOMOG on the nature of the items as well as
provide information about where they would be delivered within
the country.
</P>
<P>
The information should include detailed description of the
items, quantity to be transported, mode of transportation, date
of delivery, the point of entry and the final destination.
</P>
<P>
The conditions are contained in a memorandum to the United
Nations Children's Fund (Unicef) given by ECOMOG force Commander
Major-General Victor Malu Monday.
</P>
<P>
The conditions are listed amid reports by international aid
agencies that the deteriorating situation in embargoed Sierra
Leone may worsen the poor malnutrition rate which was as high as
10 percent before the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
Unicef's representative in Guinea, Tony Bloomberg even warned
Monday a crisis was imminent if urgent steps were not taken to
combat malnutrition and diseases in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
Bloomberg said that the regional embargo on that country
should be lifted to allow supplies to be shipped in from
neighbouring Guinea or Liberia.
</P>
<P>
According to him, there is a breakdown of all government
structures and the banking system in Sierra Leone since coupists
ousted the legitimate government of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the purchasing power of Sierra Leoneans has been
greatly reduced and many of them do not have access to health
care.
</P>
<P>
The embargo imposed on Sierra Leone was approved by the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) last month as
a means to force out the military junta led by Major Johnny
Kromah.
</P>
<P>
To enforce the embargo, ECOMOG has warned earlier that it will
attack any violators but humanitarian relief goods will be
allowed to enter Sierra Leone after the inspection and
approvement of it.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG jet fighter has attacked ships entering the port in
Freetown accused of trying to unload arms amid rice and other
goods.
</P>
<P>
The air raid of ECOMOG invited gunfire from the Sierra Leonan
army deployed to the port after the attack.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of fire has reportedly forced thousands of local
residents to flee from the port area, intensifying the situation
there.
</P>
<P>
The tense situation in Sierra Leone also led to continued
strikes from teachers of this country who have asked for the
payment of salary arrears and improvement in security.
</P>
<P>
The junta managed to pay some of the country's 18,000 teachers
in June, but many have salary arrears dating back to the civilian
regime of ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
