<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi, 74 and in power since 1978, was officially nominated as the
sole presidential candidate of his ruling Kenya African National
Union (KANU) for the impending multi-party general election.
</P>
<P>
The one-day KANU Special National Delegates Conference,
attended by more than 5,000 people from the all eight provinces
of the eastern African country, approved the nomination
unanimously with jubilant chanting this morning.
</P>
<P>
Following the approval, Moi said he was very happy to accept
the nomination, vowing to strengthen KANU and maintain the
country in peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
"KANU will continue to pursue objectives which are for the
good of this country," he said. Moi became a KANU member 42 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his commitment to constitutional reforms, saying
he is "happy with the work of IPPG (Inter-Parties Parliamentary
Group)" which presented draft plans on minimum constitutional
reforms to the parliament last week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he condemned violence erupting now and then in the
country since May, noting "street violence can only reverse the
gains Kenya has so far made.
</P>
<P>
"Bloodshed must be avoided at all costs," he vowed.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged to make more efforts to fight against
corruption and to realize sustainable economic growth. 
