<HEADLINE> Philippine Finance Chief to Attend IMF Meeting in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Finance Secretary
Roberto de Ocampo said here today that the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) meeting to be held in Hong Kong would help curb the
currency woes sweeping Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo, head of the country's delegation to the meeting on
September 21, said the delegates will discuss how to solve the
currency crisis that has been hitting not only the Philippines,
but also the other members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) since early July.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN finance ministers will see whether there is anything
they can do in concert to address the prevailing currency problems
in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will also call for the early implementation of
the World Bank's "emergency fund" to enable member economies to
stem the tide when short-term financial assistance is badly
needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the meeting is expected to provide ASEAN member
economies with the means to best guard against the deterioration
of their economies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, de Ocampo said that the Philippine government
remains committed to maintaining a sound economy, even as a slower
growth rate will be seen this year.
</P>
<P>
Economists believed that the financial meltdown in the region
will accelerate the downward spiral of the country's economy,
which slowed down to 5.9 percent in the first half of the year
compared with the 7.5 percent registered in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
Singapore, Thailand, the Philippines and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
