<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Technically Prepared for Damming of Major River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Some crucial technical
problems that would affect the blocking of the Yangtze River at
the Three Gorges in early November have been solved through
extensive studies.
</P>
<P>
Lu Youmei, General Manager of the China Yangtze River Three
Gorges Project Development Corp. which is responsible for building
the Three Gorges Dam, told reporters that they are technically
prepared for stopping the river in early November.
</P>
<P>
Chinese engineers plan to build two parallel earth-and-stone
cofferdams on the main stream to allow workers to build a dam and
electric power stations in between the two.
</P>
<P>
A number of technical problems like possible collapse or
leaking of the cofferdams have been fully studied because the main
dam will stop the Yangtze at the Three Gorges where the water is
60 m deep and flows at a speed of 14,000 cu m per second.
</P>
<P>
The problems in damming have been solved over the past
decade. Since the 1980s, engineers have made many models and
simulations for tests and have decided to put in 600,700 cu.m. of
stone to keep the depth to 30 m in the middle of the cofferdams.
</P>
<P>
A great number of equipment has been imported to stop possible
leaks. Engineers have also developed a computer-controlled command
system which can follow the process of damming and predict
problems that may crop up in construction work.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River Water Conservation Committee has worked out a
detailed dam plan through careful study of the Gezhouba Water
Control Project and projects in foreign countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
