<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Central American Countries' Move on Taiwan Issue Appreciated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China appreciated the move of
Guatemala and Dominica of not signing the motion which proposed to
discuss in the United Nations the issue of Taiwan's "return" to
the UN.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Cui Tiankai made the remarks at a
weekly press conference here today while asked to comment on the
two countries' move.
</P>
<P>
The move of these two central American countries demonstrated
that Taiwan authorities' activities of separating the country has
become increasingly unpopular, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that other countries this year signing
the relevant motion will also not support Taiwan authorities'
activities of creating "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan" in
the world by quitting signing the motion and adhering to the UN
charter and relevant resolutions of the UN General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
China attached great importance to its ties with all UN
members, including those that have not yet established diplomatic
relations with it, and would like to develop friendly and
cooperative ties with all countries on the basis of the Five
Principles of the Peaceful Co-Existence, the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
