<HEADLINE> Chinese Cities Ban Tobacco Sales to Teenagers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Health and education
authorities in the city of Weihai in east China's Shandong
province have asked tobacco retailors not to sell cigarettes to
anyone below the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
They asked department stores, grocery stores, and street
peddlers to comply with the order and put up reminders saying "No
Cigarettes Sold to Minors" nearby.
</P>
<P>
They also urged adults not to let their children buy cigarettes
for themselves or for other people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Huangpu District of Shanghai, China's largest
municipality, adopted similar measures recently in order to halt
the increase in smoking among young people, according to
Shanghai's "Xinmin Evening News".
</P>
<P>
China has laws on advertising, tobacco, and prohibiting
cigarette sales related to youth. but tobacco products are still
available for young people because of lax law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
A giant tobacco industry and about 320 million smokers make
China the largest tobacco producer and consumer in the world. One
survey has shown that Chinese males take their first puff at the
age of 20, compared with 23 in 1986.
</P>
<P>
And smoking among the people aged 15-25 rose faster than among
other age groups, according to the survey of the Chinese Academy
of Preventive Medicine last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
