<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish, Egyptian Presidents Hold talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel today held talks with his Egyptian counterpart Hosni
Mubarak in the Mediterranean port city of Alexandria which is
expected to focus on cementing ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Demirel arrived in Alexandria this morning for an one-day visit
to Egypt aimed at enhancing relations with the Arab country.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president, who was accompanied by Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem, was greeted by Mubarak at the airport.
</P>
<P>
The recent developments in the Mideast peace process,
increasing bilateral economic cooperation and Arab-Turkish ties
will top today's talks, Demirel told the Al Ahram newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here said earlier that the Mubarak-Demirel
talks would discuss means to increase their trade volume to one
billion U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
Demirel is also expected to brief Mubarak on the situation in
northern Iraq and the growing Turko-Israeli military cooperation
that will lead to joint naval maneuvers in eastern Mediterranean
in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
The planned Israeli-Turko-U.S. maneuvers provoked outcries from
Arab countries, especially Syria which sees itself as the target
of the Turkish-Israeli military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was among the most vocal critics of the war games,
which have raised concern, notably in Syria and Iran. Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said earlier that they "sent a
negative message toward the Arab countries."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Turkish summit, which was originally set for May,
was postponed in the wake of the planned naval war games.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Arabic-language daily Monday, Demirel
denied that the alliance with Israel is targeted against
Syria. "If it were so, we would not have needed cooperation with
Israel or any other state to pressure Syria," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clarifying the truth on the joint maneuvers, he said that they
were exaggerated by the Arab world beyond reality.
</P>
<P>
"We will see shortly that they are no more than exercises for
humanitarian goals, namely personnel rescue and search for the
missing," Demirel said, reiterating that they are open for Arab
countries to take part.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the exercises, Demirel also tried to justify the
large-scale Turkish incursion into northern Iraq in May, saying
that Turkey respects Iraq's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
"Turkish military presence in the north has one
objective: wiping out bases and hideouts of the outlawed Kurdish
Worker's Party (PKK)," he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, in a bid to downplay the impact of the maneuvers on
Ankara-Arab ties, has repeatedly stated that the exercises were
not directed against any country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
