<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Loses 170m Dollars on Hyacinth Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 16 (Xinhua)-- Uganda is losing 170 billions
shillings (about 170 million U.S. dollars ) per year due to the
water hyacinth, reported the local daily, The Monitor today.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of State for Agriculture, Animal Husbandry and
Fisheries Kibirige Sebunya was quoted as attributing the spread
of the weed to sientists and policy makers who he said have
remained indecisive and disunited on the methods of eradicating
the water hyacinth.
</P>
<P>
Discussions on whether to use chemicals to eliminate the
widespread weeds have lasted for years but without reaching any
agreement among scientists and departments concerned in Uganda's
government.
</P>
<P>
The weeds have now strangled 90 percent of the shoreline of
rivers and lakes, a stretch of about 2,000km.
</P>
<P>
The weeds are covering all bays of Lake Victoria, Lake Kyoga,
River Nile in Uganda and, to a small extent, Lake Albert.
</P>
<P>
About 500,000 tons of the weeds were cleaned by hyacinth
harvesters last March at the Owen Falls dam of the country's sole
hydro-electric power station.
</P>
<P>
However another 300,000 tons of the weeds have since then
grown up again at the dam site.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
