<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan Formally Begin 3rd Round of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- India and Pakistan today
attempted to narrow their differences on evolving a mechanism to
address the vexed Kashmir issue as the two countries formally
began the third round of foreign secretary level talks here, Press
Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said that the first session of the talks were
exploratory in nature with the two delegations reviewing the
progress made since the second round held in Islamabad last June.
</P>
<P>
Indian Foreign Secretary K. Raghunath and his Pakistan
counterpart Shamshad Ahmad, who arrived here on Monday, led their
respective delegations at the talks which will last until
September 18.
</P>
<P>
In a brief informal meeting on Monday, both foreign secretaries
expressed their confidence that their formal talks would mark the
beginning of a process towards the realization of cooperative and
mutually beneficial relations.
</P>
<P>
They also reiterated their firm commitment to sustaining
bilateral dialogue and give concrete shape to the mechanism for
dealing with outstanding issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to PTI, the June 23 joint statement issued by the
foreign secretaries of the two countries after their second round
of talks in Islamabad formed the basis of preliminary discussions
because the two sides had varying interpretations of the
statement.
</P>
<P>
While Pakistan maintained that the two sides had agreed in
Islamabad to set up a joint working group on Kashmir, India has
firmly contended that the issues relating to Kashmir and peace and
security were to be directly addressed at the level of foreign
secretaries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
