<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- French parliament deputies today began to study the draft law
on creating 350,000 jobs for the youth in public enterprises, which
was presented by the Minister of Employment Martine Aubry. Rightwing
opposition deputies are asking whether these ``emergency'' jobs can
last long, can compete with those of private enterprises, or really
answer the need for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
-- Some Jewish settlers, backed by dozens of Jewish activists,
moved into the heart of a Palestinian neighborhood in Jerusalem only
two steps from Mount of Olives. This challenge addressed to the
United States, which took place one day after U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright left the Mideast, jeopardized the hope of a
detente between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- After the United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
completed her first tour of the Mideast, Israel and the Palestinians
seem to be on the way of making concessions to each other. Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, saying that he was encouraged by
the ``primary positive steps'' taken by Palestinians in fighting
terrorism, released part of the Palestinian fund ``frozen'' by
Israel after the latest terrorist attacks in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
-- The Greenpeace movement and the leaders of the nuclear factory
of Cape Hague in France are engaged in another round of arms
wrestling after the ecologists discovered some nuclear stocks in the
area.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Environment Dominique Voynet said that these
stocks do not pose a threat to local environment and promised to
send a new inspection team today to investigate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
