<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Creates Information Economy Portfolio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard today announced the creation of Information Economy
portfolio in a bid to promote the country's information technology
industry.
</P>
<P>
Federal Communications Minister Richard Alston, who was awarded
today the new Information Economy portfolio, said "the government
will ensure that all Australians, from all walks of life and
wherever they live, are well positioned to benefit from the
tremendous opportunities presented by the 'Information Age'."
</P>
<P>
Following his visit to the United States earlier this year,
Howard has talked a lot about the role the information technology
industry has played in the U.S. economy, which is characterized by
fast economic growth rates, a low jobless rate and low inflation.
</P>
<P>
Australia has been troubled a high jobless rate, which has
increased to 8.7 percent in recent months, and low economic growth
rates for quite a few years.
</P>
<P>
Alston said experience in the U.S. showed this area offered
one of the greatest potentials for job growth.
</P>
<P>
"In coming years, the information economy will be a key driver
of jobs growth, and not just for jobs directly linked to
computers, but in more traditional areas such as electricians,
receptionists, security guards, builders, truck drivers and a host
of others," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The Information Economy will be a key driver to achieving
dramatic increases in social and economic prosperity into the 21st
century," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Australia was well-placed to take advantage of the
opportunities arising from the new information economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We have one of the most rapid take-ups of new technologies, a
well-educated workforce, one of the most competitive
telecommunications regimes and a world-class telecommunications
infrastructure, a stable political and economic environment ...
geographically close to and in the same time zones as the
Asia-Pacific," the minister explained.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
