<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Middle East businesses have been urged to increase
their share in the 30 billion U.S. dollars spent annually on
procurement of goods and services by different United Nations
agencies and international development banks.
</P>
<P>
Edward de Broe-Ferguson, chairman of the British speciality
program management firm, Tamarisk, said here Monday that the
businesses in the region currently share less than one percent of
the procurement by those organizations.
</P>
<P>
Delivering speech at the Amman Chamber of Industry, he added
that the U.N. Intra Agency Procurement Services Office had
expressed a desire to have more Middle East companies as its
regular suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Broe-Ferguson said Tamarisk has in the past two years
organized conferences annually aimed at expanding the number of
Middle East suppliers to the U.N. by increasing awareness of the
procedures needed to tender for U.N. contracts.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Two commercial banks of Saudi Arabia, the United
Saudi Commercial Bank and Saudi Cairo Bank announced last weekend
that they had merged into one, named the Saudi United Bank,
according to reports of Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The merger deal has brought the new bank up to the third
largest one in the kingdom with a capital of 653.3 million
U.S. dollars and an asset of 8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Prince Al-Waleed Bin Talal, a major share holder of the bank,
became the first board chairman of the Saudi United Bank.
</P>
<P>
He bought large shares of the United Saudi Commercial Bank in
1988 and took in 33.4 percent of the shares of the Saudi Cairo
Bank in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The largest bank in Saudi Arabia is Al-Ahli Bank with a capital
of 1.6 billion dollars and the second is Al-Riyadh Bank with a
capital of 1.06 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Gas reserves in the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) states are expected to rise from the present 20 trillion to
28.7 trillion cubic meters in the next few years, Yusif Abdullah,
director of the GCC oil and gas secretariat has said.
</P>
<P>
GCC's gas reserves will account for 20.5 percent of the current
140 trillion proven reserves of the world, he was quoted as saying
in the latest issue of the Oil and Arab Cooperation magazine.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, GCC's reserves increased by 115 percent to reach about
20 trillion cubic meters from the reserves of 9.8 trillion cubic
meters in 1986, which had a share of 14.3 percent of the world
proven reserves.
</P>
<P>
GCC shares recently 4.6 percent of the gas sold in the world
market. During the last decade, GCC's gas production rose by 7.5
percent annually, Abdullah said, estimating that gas consumption
grew in the last few years by 7.6 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
GCC, established in 1981, groups Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates, Kuwait, Oman, Bahrain and Qatar, which also have 48
percent of the world proven oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwaiti Oil Minister Issa Al-Mazidi has
predicted a high global oil demand for the last quarter of this
year in view of the fall in petroleum reserves of industrialized
countries.
</P>
<P>
Quoted in today's Arabic daily Al-Rai Al-Aam in an interview,
the minister said that the world oil demand for the period is
likely to reach 76 million barrels per day, more than three
percent higher than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
He said he has information that "the petroleum reserves in a
number of industrial states and the United States fell during the
past three months."
</P>
<P>
The industrialized states would feed their reserves "as they
usually do every winter, thus resulting in the increase of
demand," Al-Mazidi said.
</P>
<P>
Experts expect the prices would strengthen in the last quarter,
but saying they would not reach the level for the same period of
1996 when prices soared to nearly 23 U.S. dollars in the world
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
