<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Party Congress as seen by Ordinary Chinese (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- At a meeting on Saturday
evening in east China, Wu Renbao, Party secretary of Huaxi
village, is telling villagers about the guidelines of Comrade
Jiang Zemin's speech at the opening of the 15th National Congress
of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
"No changes have been made in the Party guidelines and
policies," he tells the 1,000 people gathered in Huaxi Village in
Jiangyin city of Jiangsu province, "If there were changes, they
were to emancipate our minds and deepen the reforms. The changes
are to make things better and better."
</P>
<P>
The village's most rapid development has come since the 14th
Party Congress in 1992. What it has earned in the past five years
is equal to what it earned in the entire 30-year period before the
Congress. Its collective assets have gone from 500 million yuan
(60 million US dollars) in 1992 to 1.2 billion yuan (145 million
U.S. dollars) now.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the villagers shared their ideas about Jiang's report
with the others, saying that they saw new economic opportunities
coming from the Congress and agreeing that Huaxi must look for
chances. They say that they will build their area into an even
more beautiful paradise for farmers.
</P>
<P>
At a job information center in Shanghai, a middle-aged woman
named Bao Cuiying is job hunting in front of a computer. "The
issue of reform and development of the state-owned enterprises
discussed by the Congress has long been expected," she said,
noting she was glad to hear that Comrade Jiang called for positive
and practical steps to be taken to protect laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China will follow up on its re-employment project by
offering job training and more employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"What Comrade Jiang said in the report is what we care most
about," Bao said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Party Congress as Seen by Ordinary Chinese (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hu Kangzhen, a longtime employee of the Anshan Iron and Steel
Company, one of China's largest iron and steel complexes, shared
the idea of new reforms of the state-owned enterprises by relying
on the working class, in Jiang's report.
</P>
<P>
"The factory is the workers' home. To implement Jiang Zemin's
ideas is to use our own hands to revive our company without asking
for help or assistance from the state," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Qianjiang, another employee of the company, said that
since the beginning of the 15th Congress on September 12, daily
iron smelting capacity at the iron works has been 22,250 tons, a
record. Noting that workers all came to work early and left late
because, he said "we know very well that the development of the
company is related to the personal involvement of every worker."
</P>
<P>
Qiaodun Brewery in Zhejiang province's Wenzhou is the city's
first company to experiment with the share-holding system. The
venture was first established in 1985 by 81 farmers. Wu Zuzhong,
its director, was elected by shareholders.
</P>
<P>
When the venture proved to be a great success in the late
1980s, the city began to let more ventures become share-holders.
</P>
<P>
Wu said he had discussed Comrade Jiang's speech with the
workers and, "since the Party central committee has confirmed the
share-holding enterprises, we will run our venture better without
worrying about a change in policies."
</P>
<P>
Li Shanfen, deputy manager of Shanghai's China No.1 Pencil
Company Ltd., said that Jiang's report was a scientific
elaboration of the share-holding system, a form of organizing
capital.
</P>
<P>
Li cited the share-holding system as an effective way to
develop state-owned enterprises, and said her company became a
share-holding company in 1992 and its total assets have risen
10-fold over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The 15th CPC National Congress has become a hot topic on
campuses, too. Huang Yingyi, a senior student of prestigious
Qinghua University, told reporters that she and her roommates all
talked the congress deep into the night over the past few days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
