<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diary of Party Congress Delegates (Sept. 16) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- (At Xinhua's request, some
delegates to the current 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) write what they see, discuss and think during
the congress in the form of a diary, which we think will provide
outsiders with some information about this major event. The
following diary, the sixth of its kind, was written by Tian Peifa,
principal of a poor village school in southwest China's Guizhou
Province. -- Ed.)
</P>
<P>
I almost jumped to joy when Comrade Jiang Zemin said in his
report delivered at the opening session of the 15th National Party
Congress that China will give priority to education in its
development strategy.
</P>
<P>
In the evening of September 12, the day the Party congress
opened, we congress delegates were invited to visit Tian'anmen
Rostrum. The glittering lights in Tian'anmen Square and smiling
faces of visitors reminded me of the children and teachers in my
village school. How I wished they could have come with me to see
the picturesque scene in the country's capital city.
</P>
<P>
At that thought, I bought each teacher a souvenir coin bearing
the logo of Tian'anmen Rostrum to encourage them to work harder
for the Party so that they could come to visit Beijing.
</P>
<P>
My county is situated at the foot of the Wuling Mountain,
northeast Guizhou Province. Bordering Hunan and Chongqing, my
county, inhabited by 560,000-odd people, many of whom are of the
Miao ethnic group, is one of the country's poorest counties.
</P>
<P>
The town where I come from has only one junior middle school
built in the 1970s. Only 100 out of every 400 to 500 primary
school graduates can continue their study in the middle school.
</P>
<P>
To accommodate more children to continue their study, the
county and township governments tried hard to raise funds for
education.
</P>
<P>
In Dapeng Village, Niulang Town, where I have been working,
villagers raised 70,000 yuan for the construction of a primary
school. Early this year, the county and town governments set aside
another 160,000 yuan to build a middle school. The county
government has decided to build another modern high school for
people of ethnic minorities. I'm excited at the thought. My home
village is hopeful although it is still poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
