<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Expected to Rise in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Limited supply and increased
demand were expected to spur the eastern market indicator for wool
up almost 9 percent to an average 483 U.S. cents a clean kilogram
over the 1997-98 fiscal year beginning July 1, the official chief
commodity forecaster said here today.
</P>
<P>
The latest forecast in the September quarterly commodity
publication of the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource
Economics (ABARE) is well up from the 650 Australian cents (469
U.S. cents)/kg prediction of the June quarter.
</P>
<P>
ABARE noted the eastern market indicator was likely to fall
from current levels.
</P>
<P>
"The higher average price is expected to result from increased
demand for raw wool, a lower Australian dollar and little change
in the quantity of Australian wool supplied to the market," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The average price was tipped to have a 75 percent chance of
being in the 458-519 U.S. cents/kg range, reflecting market
uncertainty and fluctuating factors influencing supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
The western market indicator was forecast to rise 7.5 percent
to 444 U.S. cents, up from the 600 Australian cent (433 U.S.
cents) prediction of the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said Australian shorn wool production should reach
650,000 tons in 1997-98, as increased sales from private stocks
were offset by lower Wool International sales.
</P>
<P>
Despite increased competition from cotton and synthetics, raw
wool demand was anticipated to rise slightly due to rebuilding of
pipeline stocks and improved retail demand in key wool consuming
countries.
</P>
<P>
Fine wool exports were expected to rise, especially to Italy
and China.
</P>
<P>
In China, overall stocks at some stages in the processing
pipeline were high, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Raw wool demand could pick up as stocks ran down, probably
leading to total wool use remaining unchanged in China on 1996-97
levels, it said.
</P>
<P>
Raw wool demand in Japan was expected to continue to improve as
restocking continued.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 300 Killed, 60,000 Displaced in W. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- At least 300 people have
been killed, 60,000 displaced in the district of Kasese in
western Uganda, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing the records of local councils in the district, The New
Vision said that more than 200 people have been murdered since
last November when the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) rebels
invaded into the district from former Zaire. Other 80 people have
been killed in ADF raids on the villages in the district.
</P>
<P>
Moses Otwiili, an officer of the criminal investigation
department in the district, noted that the records are not
complete, with many murder cases not recorded.
</P>
<P>
Bamusede Bwambale, a local council official in the district,
told a gathering Sunday that there are some 60,000 displaced
people in the district.
</P>
<P>
"Families are starving almost to death and in some areas
children are dying," he said.
</P>
<P>
ADF is a rebel group haunting in Kasese district which has
some 350 members now, a recent official report said.
</P>
<P>
It invaded Uganda from former Zaire last November with its
1,500 fighters. Recent reports indicated that some of its
remnants are trying to seek a hideout in east Congo under the
circumstance of renewed fighting in the area between the
government troops and some rebels here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
