<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Moves to Protect Ozone Layer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will soon pass a law
to regulate the importation of secondhand fridges and compressors
with chloro-floro carbon (CFC) refrigerants gases which have been
responsible for the depletion of ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted Environment Minister William
Harrington as saying here Monday that "the task ahead of us calls
for behavioral change in terms of industrial production
techniques, the need to ensure importation and purchase of
friendly items like CFC-free fridges, refraining from acquiring
secondhand fridges and fridge components while using CFC
refrigerants."
</P>
<P>
He said the government has raised alarm at the large
quantities of refrigerators which are environmentally unfriendly
being dumped in Zambia from European countries.
</P>
<P>
The trend of importing environmentally unfriendly technology
and chemicals must come to an end, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia is a signatory to the U.N. Montreal Protocol
which restricts use of chlorine- and bromide-containing chemicals
and Zambia should abide by the rules.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that since the problem of ozone layer
depletion has become a real threat to the environment, animals
and human beings, it is inevitable that there are concerted
efforts in fighting against the trend.
</P>
<P>
Harrington called for total cooperation from the entrepreneurs
and industries concerned if the government's efforts to
contribute to the preservation of ozone layer are to be realized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
