<HEADLINE> Taiwan-born Party Delegate Impressed by China's Changes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Today is the Mid-Autumn
Festival, a traditional Chinese festival for family reunions. Lin
Mingyue, a CPC delegate, who was born in Taiwan and educated in
the United States, tells her story.
</P>
<P>
Lin, who returned to China 17 years ago, was impressed that her
motherland has become stronger and stronger day by day and she is
proud of her participation in bringing about such changes.
</P>
<P>
Lin returned to China with her husband and son in 1980 when
many Chinese youth were fighting to get an American visa. "It's my
emotion and confidence in China that prompted me to return to my
motherland," said Lin.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, Deng Xiaoping's visit to the United States stirred a
China boom in the US. Lin was then confident that China, which
began reforms and opening-up, would become stronger in several
years to come and the cause of the peaceful reunification of the
motherland would be surely achieved.
</P>
<P>
In December 1979, Lin and her husband, Fan Zengsheng, applied
for a visa with the Chinese Embassy in the United States although
each of them had a secured job in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as we returned to Shanghai, we applied with the local
government to give up my son's American nationality and join the
Chinese nationality," Lin recalled.
</P>
<P>
"But unexpectedly, the government official who received us
advised us not to do so, saying that it would be more convenient
for him to visit our relatives in the United States and Taiwan
later with his American visa," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Though it is a trifle, it moved very much. this showed the
government's care about and confidence in us Taiwan compatriots,"
she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
