<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan-born Party Delegate Impressed by China's Changes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After Lin settled down in Shanghai, she started making
preparations for an information center in Shanghai Port Authority.
She has since then served as director and senior engineer of the
center which employs more than 50 people.
</P>
<P>
Lin's engagement with the Chinese Communist Party dated back to
June 30, 1981, when she and her husband were invited to a party
marking the 60th anniversary of the founding of the CPC sponsored by
the Shanghai Port Authority.
</P>
<P>
"The celebrations were solemn," she recalled. Later, she
attended lectures about the goals and obligations of the CPC and
carefully studied the Party Constitution.
</P>
<P>
"I was especially touched by the fine moral character and
dedication of the Party members of my center. And a year later, my
husband and I handed in our applications to join the Party," she
said.
</P>
<P>
In March 1985, Lin was admitted into the Party and several
months later, her husband, now deputy head of Shanghai Port
Authority, also joined the Party.
</P>
<P>
Lin owed her success in career to her good luck, excellent
opportunity and her own dedication to work. "I'm lucky that my
bosses have attached great importance to science and technology
and know how to judge and use people," she said, adding that
China's reforms and opening-up have provided her a chance to
give full play to her talent.
</P>
<P>
In the past several years, Lin and her husband were often sent
abroad for public missions. "I was the head almost in every
mission or study and I have the final say in some negotiations,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
In 1986, Lin went back to the United States with her husband
and son to join their family members in the States. She was told
later that the Taiwan authorities had tried several times to
persuade her to go back to work in Taiwan through her younger
brother.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, her father died in Taiwan. And Lin went back to Taiwan
where she had left for more than 20 years. But her husband's entry
was rejected by the Taiwan authorities because of his position,
and for this, she still feels regretful today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
