<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Oil Minister Predicts Higher World Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Oil Minister Issa
Al-Mazidi has predicted a high global oil demand for the last
quarter of this year in view of the fall in petroleum reserves of
industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
Quoted in today's Arabic daily Al-Rai Al-Aam in an interview,
the minister said that the world oil demand for the period is
likely to reach 76 million barrels per day, more than three
percent higher than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
He said he has information that "the petroleum reserves in a
number of industrial states and the United States fell during the
past three months."
</P>
<P>
The industrialized states would feed their reserves "as they
usually do every winter, thus resulting in the increase of
demand," Al-Mazidi said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "this situation will result in maintaining the
current prices this month and the following month."
</P>
<P>
Oil prices have remained strong despite the return of
U.N. sanction-hit Iraq to the market and a slackening in seasonal
demand in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
During the first eight months of 1997, the price of OPEC's
basket of seven crudes averaged around 18.9 U.S. dollars per
barrel, one of their highest levels in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Experts expect the prices would strengthen in the last quarter,
but saying they would not reach the level for the same period of
1996 when prices soared to nearly 23 U.S. dollars in the world
market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Al-Mazidi noted "the Iraqi petroleum sold on the
market affects prices" marginally.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal which came into effect last
December, the U.N. allows Baghdad to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars
worth of oil in six months to buy food and medicine badly needed
sanction-ridden Iraq. The deal has been renewed for another six
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
