<HEADLINE> 10 Dengue Cases Confirmed in Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The total number of dengue
patients in the Indian capital of New Delhi has increased to 10 as
two more confirmed cases being reported in a major government
hospital, The Hindustan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Kiran Dambalkar, chief medical officer of the Delhi Dengue
Control Cell, said the All India Institute of Medical Sciences
(AIIMS) has confirmed that two Delhi residents, a 19-year-old girl
and a 28-year-old man, were suffering dengue.
</P>
<P>
According to the Dengue Control Cell, the number of suspected
dengue cases in the capital is 70.
</P>
<P>
The doctors are reportedly sending all fever cases for testing
because the local authorities have threatened to prosecute doctors
who do not report dengue patients.
</P>
<P>
The dengue virus is transmitted into the human body by the bite
of the aedes mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
An epidemic of the disease in New Delhi last year claimed
nearly 300 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
