<HEADLINE> Turkish President Leaves for Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel left here today for Egypt on an one-day working visit
aimed at expanding bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the press before his departure, Demirel said that
he will discuss with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak means of
further enhancing cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that they will also exchange views over the latest
development in the stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish leader declined to say whether he will explain to
his Egyptian counterpart the Israeli-Turkish-U.S. joint naval
maneuvers scheduled to start on November 16 in the eastern
Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here, however, believed that the joint
naval war games are the top priority on Demirel's agenda.
</P>
<P>
The planned tripartite exercise had triggered strong
criticism among Egypt and other Arab nations in the region.
</P>
<P>
Demirel called off a planned visit to Egypt in May due to
alleged technical reasons. At that time, Turkey was accused by
some Arab nations, including Egypt, of violating Iraq's
sovereignty when Ankara launched a massive cross-border military
strike agaisnt the outlawed Kurdish Worker's Party (PKK) in
northern Iraq. 
</P>
