<HEADLINE> China's Largest SEZ Starts New Undertakings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Hainan, China's largest
special economic zone (SEZ), has set new goals for further
development as encouraged by the report Jiang Zemin delivered to
the on-going Party congress.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Wang Xiaofeng, deputy governor of
the southernmost Chinese island province, said that Hainan will
step up the re-organization of state sector and transformation
through shareholding so as to improve economic performance of the
state sector.
</P>
<P>
Wang said Hainan has been hit by fund shortage, which Wang
deemed as a superficial factor in its economic development. The
key reason for this, he said, is the poor quality in economic
operations.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy governor, the province, which was a
paradise of speculations in early 1990s, had gone out of "bubble
economy". Though its economic growth has slowed down, the quality
has greatly improved.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of the construction sector in GDP has dropped.
More multinational companies have flocked to Hainan with more
foreign investment diverted from real estate to industrial
development, he said.
</P>
<P>
After five years of structural readjustment, he said,
Hainan has full capacities for large scale development. The
province has become one of the best provinces with surplus
power output, most condensed highway system and best telecom
facilities, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
