<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dairy, Beef Exports Expected to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The value of Australia's
dairy product exports is expected to rise 17 percent this year to
a record of just under 2 billion Australian dollars (1.44 billion
US dollars), an official forecaster said today.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics
(ABARE) today attributed the increase in the value of dairy
exports to the expected growth in the world dairy product prices.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has forecast a 17.3 percent increase in the value of
dairy product exports, on last year's exports, to 1.998 billion
Australian dollars (1.442 billion US dollars) for 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
"Reflecting the expected growth in the world dairy prices,
Australia's returns from exporting butter, cheese and milk powder
are forecast to increase by 3 percent in 1997," ABARE said in its
September quarter commodity publication.
</P>
<P>
Butter exports are expected to increase 9 percent in value to
113 million US dollars, cheese exports by 9.3 percent to 212
million US dollars, whole milk powder by 7.5 percent to 103
million US dollars and skim milk powder by 8.1 percent to 173
million US dollars, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
ABARE today also predicted Australian lamb prices were set to
decline 5 percent to 149 US cents a kilogram, mainly due to higher
production.
</P>
<P>
Dry conditions were expected to result in continued high
slaughtering of sheep and cattle over 1997-98, it explained.
</P>
<P>
It said depreciation of the Australian dollar and tightening of
feeder cattle supply in the United States were expected to boost
beef prices.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian saleyard indicator price for beef is forecast
to increase by 13 US cents a kilogram to average 122 US cents a
kilogram in 1997-98," the current financial year beginning July 1,
1997.
</P>
<P>
Live cattle exports, sourced mainly from northern Australia
for Southeast Asia markets, were expected to jump about 8 percent
in 1997-98 to a record 930,000 head.
</P>
<P>
Australian beef exports to Japan were only expected to
increase 3 percent in 1997-98 due to higher US exports of grainfed
beef, favored by importers, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Beef exports to the US, Indonesia and the Philippines were
forecast to rise by 5 percent, 7.5 percent and 7.5 percent,
respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
