<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 08:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Turkish-U.S. War Games to Start November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The controversial
Israeli-Turkish-U.S. joint naval maneuvers are to start on
November 16 off the Israeli coast in the eastern Mediterranean,
local newspaper Turkish Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted reliable military officials, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, as saying that warships belonging to the
three countries are expected to gather at the Israeli port of
Haifa on November 14 and 15.
</P>
<P>
The joint military exercises will end on November 23,
according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
The tripartite war games are aimed at improving cooperation
among the three navies in search-and-rescue operations, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
A Turkish military delegation will visit Israel next month to
make specific arrangements for the exercises, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Although earlier statements said that the war games are open to
other countries, the military officials declined to comment on it.
</P>
<P>
The planned maneuvers had prompted severe criticism from some
Arab nations, which accused Turkey, also a Muslim country, of
betraying the interests of the Muslim world by siding with Arab's
political rival of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been trying to assure its Arab neighbors that the
tripartite exercises are not directed against any other country,
saying it is "a search-and-rescue operation" devoid of any
strategic importance.
</P>
<P>
"We think that the reactions which emerged are probably based
on the fact that the real objectives of the exercises are not well
understood," a Turkish Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman has said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey signed two defense and military agreements with Israel
last year to allow, among other things, both countries' planes to
train in each other's airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price Rise Down in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region
reported a drop in the retail price increase to 3.9 percent in
July from 5.2 percent earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the retail price index and cost of living
index dropped 3.1 and 2.2 percentage points, respectively, on a
year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
The price of food, cigarettes, beverage and drinks, Chinese and
Western medicines, machinery, and electronic products dropped a
great deal.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the drop in price increase to the good
economic conditions and the declining inflation rate, since 85
percent of the region's supplies are brought in from other parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The adequate supplies have also played a role in bringing down
prices, they noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
