<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Wheat Output to Fall to 16.2 Million Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Australia was poised to
produce a wheat crop of just 16.2 million tons in the 1997-98
fiscal year (beginning July 1, 1997), about 3 million tons less
than hoped for in March, the Australian government's chief
commodity forecaster said today.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics
(ABARE)' forecast in its September quarter commodity publication
was unchanged on its Crop Report estimate released earlier this
month, which blamed widespread dry conditions for the wheat drop.
</P>
<P>
Wheat exports are tipped to reap 2.486 billion Australian
dollars (1.794 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997-98, down from the
2.509 billion Australian dollar (1.811 billion dollars) estimate
of the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
The pool return for Australian standard white wheat in the
current fiscal year was still expected to reach about 140 U.S.
dollars, down 3.61 U.S. dollars a ton from last year's return.
</P>
<P>
ABARE said the main world indicator price, the U.S. hard red
winter wheat, was forecast to average between 148 U.S. dollars and
180 U.S. dollars a ton in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The most likely outcome was for prices to average 5 percent
lower than last year at 170 U.S. dollars a ton, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Despite large wheat crops in China, the U.S. and Europe, lower
production in Australia, Canada and Argentina was expected to
result in slightly lower world production in 1997-98 of 575
million tons, it said.
</P>
<P>
Australia achieved a record 23.6 million tons in wheat
production in 1996-97, the previous fiscal year ending June 30,
1997.
</P>
<P>
ABARE today sharply revised downwards the amount of rice
expected to be produced in Australia over 1997-98, citing static
world prices and substantially lower water allocations expected in
the state of rice-producing New South Wales for the unspecified
fall.
</P>
<P>
In its June quarter forecasts, it believed rice production
would remain at 1.4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
It said good returns and abundant water supplies should enable
Australia to produce a record 403,000 hectares in cotton planting
in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
"Assuming average seasonal conditions and average yields, a
harvest of 606,000 tons of lint is forecast for 1997-98 (up 5.2
percent from 1996-97)," the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The bureau also said Australia's sugar production and exports
are both expected to rise this year following falls in production
in other major sugar producing areas.
</P>
<P>
Sugar production is expected to rise 3.3 percent from 5.4
million tons in 1996-97 to 5.6 million tons this year in Australia
and the country's sugar exports are forecast to rise over 5
percent in 1997-98 valued at 1.15 billion US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
