<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Loses 60 Million Dollars to Cassava Mosaic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Uganda loses 60 million U.S.
Dollars every year due to the widespread cassava mosaic disease,
reported the local daily, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Cassava is a staple food in Uganda, and ranks second to
bananas in production acreage and per capita consumption.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, over 60 percent of the farming
community in the country depends on cassava for food.
</P>
<P>
The paper said more than 60,000 hectares in the country
equivalent to 600,000 tons of cassava are destroyed by the
disease each year.
</P>
<P>
The disease has spread to all parts of the country, especially
in Kabarole district in the west, the paper said, adding that the
farmers there have appealed to the Ministry of Agriculture to
supply them with cassava mosaic resistant cuttings, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the food and agriculture organization's estimate,
Uganda's cassava output per year is about 3.9 million tons in
recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
