<HEADLINE> Joint Ventures Economic Key in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Overseas-backed businesses in
east China's Jiangsu province have had an annual average increase in
their taxes of 72.8 percent over the past five years, making them a
major contributor to local revenues.
</P>
<P>
These enterprises paid nearly six billion yuan (723 million US
dollars) in taxes and had made 700 million yuan in profits last
year, accounting for 13 percent of the province's total revenue.
</P>
<P>
The province had more than 23,000 overseas-backed firms by the
end of 1996, and 67 percent have started production. They had 9.2
billion yuan (1.1 billion US dollars) in exports last year, making
up nearly half the province's total.
</P>
<P>
A growing influx in overseas investment has come from Jiangsu's
efforts to improve its investment climate. It has spent more than
60 billion yuan (7.2 billion US dollars) on transportation,
telecommunications, energy, and other infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
