<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Appeals for Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has called on the donor community for emergency
food aid and financial support to curb serious food shortage
facing the country.
</P>
<P>
The president made the appeal Monday while briefing heads of
diplomatic missions based in Dar es Salaam on food situation in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said that his country needs 103,600 tons of maize and
pulses and some 5,000 million shillings (eight million US
dollars) for food distribution.
</P>
<P>
About 1.5 million people in the country will need relief aid
until April next year, according to Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa told the diplomats that food shortage was caused by
drought which hit the country during the 1996/97 season,
describing it as the worst in the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
He said that the domestic food production is estimated to be
5.5 million tons which is about 88 percent of the requirement.
</P>
<P>
"This is a shortfall that is real and imminent, and one which
has been verified by the joint assessment mission that included
representatives from WFP, USAID and FAO. this is a shortfall that
has to be met from external sources," Mkapa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
