<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Plans Crackdown on Border Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
planned a crackdown on smuggling to protect the domestic market
from being gutted by contraband that posed a threat to the
national economy, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
It will be a well-coordinated drive, to be launched shortly,
said a senior security official, adding that a coordination team
comprising various agencies like the National Security
Intelligence, police and customs is under consideration.
</P>
<P>
To control illegal cross border trade, the government is also
taking step to revive the joint checkpoints of various
law-enforcing agencies which were folded up in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken several other steps to strengthen the
anti-smuggling drive, including raising 15 new Border Out Posts
(BOPs), constitution of a committee to amend the anti-smuggling
laws, setting up central information cell in the capital Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult to police the 4,427 kilometer border with 496
BOPs manned by about 14 personnel each to cover 8 to 10 kilometers
between two posts," said the official of Bangladesh Rifles, the
border security force of this India-surround country.
</P>
<P>
In this case, anti-smuggling mission could attain its goal by
mobilizing people's cooperation, amending anti-smuggling laws and
increasing security forces, he viewed.
</P>
<P>
People living in the border areas are involved in the smuggling
profession due to unemployment problem, but, on the other hand,
people in those areas also help provide information about
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
"Without information it is very difficult to seize or recover
three major items -- gold, heroin and firearms," said the security
official.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Rifles recovered smuggled goods worth about 1.56
billion taka (about 35.5 million U.S. dollars) in 1995 and about
1.21 billion taka (27.5 million dollars) in 1996. And in the
current year, until August, it stood at 890 million taka (20.2
million dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
