<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Tea Exports Up 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's tea exports
during the first seven months of this year registered a 20 percent
increase in value over the same period last year, local press
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
From January to July, Sri Lanka exported 22.1 billion rupees
(370 million U.S. dollars) of tea to the world market, compared
with 18.4 billion rupees (312 million dollars) of the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 148 million kilograms of tea were sold to the world
market in the period, up 6.7 percent over the corresponding period
last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tea prices also rose from 133 rupees (2.25 dollars)
per kilogram in 1996 to 149.4 rupees (2.5 dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) continues to be
the biggest market for Sri Lanka's tea, followed by Turkey, the
United Arab Emirates and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Tea is one of Sri Lanka's main export items and the source of
25 percent of its export earnings. The total tea exports last year
were 244 million kilograms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
