<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africans Urged to Fight Female Genital Mutilation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 16 (xinhua) -- African countries have
strongly been advised to adopt clear and constant policies for
the abolition of Female Genital Mutilation (FMG) and other
harmful practices in the continent.
</P>
<P>
This was the consensus of representatives of the member states
of the Inter-African Committee on Traditional Practices affecting
the health of women and children, Kuwayawaya Stephen,
representative from Tanzania's Dodoma Chapter of the committee,
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kuwayawaya has just come back after taking part in a meeting
of the committee that was convened in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, last
week.
</P>
<P>
The Addis Ababa meeting which brought together prominent
lawyers, legislators, and judges proposed establishment of a
ministry to co-ordinate and monitor implementation of national
policy through a multi-sectoral approach.
</P>
<P>
Kuwayawaya said that the meeting also called for a concrete
mechanism to fight all forms of violence against women.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the African nations were further told to
organize and strengthen existing structures and create conducive
environment for effective enforcement of laws against women.
</P>
<P>
The countries must also organize strong community for
education programs involving village and religious leaders and
encourage non-governmental organizations (NGOs) fighting the
violence against women and children.
</P>
<P>
The meeting made a draft report on FGM and abuse of women and
children rights before being forwarded to the OAU to adopt a
formal declaration on the violence, according to Kuwayawaya.
</P>
<P>
It was resolved that women genital mutilation should be
eliminated by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 33 countries participated in the meeting
from September 10 to 12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
