<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People of Beijing Turn in Ancient Bricks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's residents have
found some 60,000 ancient bricks since last October and turned
them in for a wall-restoration project.
</P>
<P>
Beijing used to have a wall around it that was put up during
the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644). Most of the wall was pulled down in
the 1960s as a result of massive urban expansion.
</P>
<P>
Many of the city's residents still regret the damages done to
the renowned historic site, which would have become a tourist
spot, so they began a campaign to turn in any old bricks they
found lying scattered about the city.
</P>
<P>
The activity has involved tens of thousands of residents,
including some foreigners working in the city. An exhibition of
the co-operative endeavor is being held to encourage people to
return the relics protection, "Beijing Daily" reports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
