<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Down in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' trade deficit
in the first seven months of this year was down by 6.4 percent
from a year earlier as the country's exports continued to rise
during the period, the National Statistics Office said today.
</P>
<P>
In a report issued here, the office said imports rose by 11
percent to 20.501 billion U.S. dollars in the first seven months
of the year from 18.468 billion dollars in the same period last
year, while exports grew by 22.1 percent to 13.767 billion dollars
from 11.276 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The balance of trade in goods resulted in a deficit of 6.734
billion dollars which was down by 6.4 percent from 7.192 billion
dollars a year ago," it said.
</P>
<P>
The office said the merchandise trade increased by 15.2 percent
as two-way trade transactions for the first seven months of 1997
reached 34.269 billion dollars from 29.744 billion dollars a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
In July only, the office said, imports rose by 11.8 percent to
3.174 billion dollars from 2.839 billion dollars in the
corresponding period of last year while exports grew by 22 percent
to 2.067 billion dollars from 1.694 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit for July was 1.107 billion dollars, a 3.3
percent drop from 1.145 billion dollars last year, it said.
</P>
<P>
This was the fifth consecutive month of decline in the
country's trade deficit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
