<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Hopes to Strengthen Cooperation With World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Valern
Pustovoitenko said today that Ukraine hopes to enhance cooperation
with the World Bank in energy, the coal industry and agricultural
reforms, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko told Johannes Linn, visiting vice president of
the World Bank, that due to the present inability of Ukrainians to
make utility payments, Ukraine cannot raise energy prices as
required by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World
Bank, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine ranks sixth among the 10 main debtors of the World
Bank, from which it has received 989.6 million U.S. dollars in
loans and 220 million dollars in cash deposits.
</P>
<P>
Linn said the World Bank will allocate 500 million dollars in
loans to Ukraine before the end of this year as soon as both sides
reach agreements on a series of cooperation programs.
</P>
<P>
There are also reports that within the past five years, the
World Bank has promised funding for more than 30 projects in
Ukraine, and the total amount of loans will eventually reach 5
billion dollars, including 1.5 billion dollars on eight projects
under construction.
</P>
<P>
Linn, who arrived here today, also met with Ukrainian President
Leonid Kuchma on structural reforms of the country's energy
sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
