<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Train Accident Toll Rises to 81 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from the
train accident in India's Madhya Pradesh has gone up to 81 as more
bodies were recovered in rescue operations on Monday, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
However, unofficial sources put the death toll at about 100.
</P>
<P>
Five coaches of an express train fell from a bridge on Hansdeo
river in Bislaspur district, Madhya Pradesh on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Indian Railway Minister Ram Vilas Paswan said on Monday that
the accident could have been averted if the train driver had been
given timely information about track repair at the accident site.
</P>
<P>
He said the track repair near the site violated instructions
that no such work should be carried out after 5:00 p.m. The
accident occurred at about 6:50 p.m.
</P>
<P>
According to an official release, the discontinuity in track
was the main cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
About 230 passengers, who were injured in the accident, were
admitted to local hospitals on Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
