<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Introduces 500,000 Lire Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Italy today issued a
new bill of 500,000 lire, the equivalent of some 290 U.S. dollars
and five times the value of Italy's previously largest banknote.
</P>
<P>
The 500,000 lire bill, which bears a self-portrait of the
Italian Renaissance artist Raphael and two other paintings by him,
was presented by Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi in the central
Italian city of Urbino, the artist's home town.
</P>
<P>
The Italian central bank printed 30 million of the new bills,
which will reach the public Tuesday and are expected to reduce the
total number of bills in circulation by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new bank note immediately incurred criticism and doubts, as
Italians have worried that issuing new bills will result in much
inflation, before Italy adopts the European single currency in
1999, according to local press reports.
</P>
<P>
The local press said people were also concerned that the
currency is so big in face value that it might bring about
inconvenience in use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
