<HEADLINE> Tremors Hit Indonesia's Bengkulu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A tremor measuring 5.7 on the
Richter Scale shook Bengkulu, capital of Indonesia's Bengkulu
province and its surroundings on Monday, reports reaching here
today said.
</P>
<P>
The tremor occurred at 1:27 p.m. local time, following a quake
two days earlier, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Its epicenter was 100 kilometers deep in the Indian ocean and
some 145 kilometers southeast of Manna, according to the
geophysical station in Kepahyang, Bengkulu.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports of casualties or damage.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, a quake logged at 5.3 on the Richter Scale also
hit the region.
</P>
<P>
"Theoretically, the two tremors have been triggered by the
transition from the dry to rainy season, which is estimated to
start early in October," experts were quoted as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
