<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economic Ministers Halt Property Rescue Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Thai economic ministers have
turned down a plan to set up a 30 billion baht (833 million U.S.
dollars) fund to rescue the ailing property sector through the
government-owned National Housing Authority (NHA).
</P>
<P>
At their routine council meeting on Monday, the economic
ministers believed that the plan, proposed by the Interior
Ministry, would violate a condition signed with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), according to the nation today.
</P>
<P>
One of the conditions imposed by the IMF is that the public
sector cannot buy or assist private sector businesses.
</P>
<P>
The proposed fund was designed for October 1, with a plan to
buy houses and buildings from property developers for resale to
low-income earners.
</P>
<P>
The NHA has been ordered to discuss the matter further with
Deputy Prime Minister Virabongsa Ramangura and Finance Minister
Thanong Bidaya and to report the conclusion back to the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's property sector has been in an ailing condition for
about four years. As a result, commercial banks and finance firms
are ridden with huge amounts of bad loans owned by developers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
