<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia, Croatia Sign Agreements on Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia and Croatia
signed a package of agreements on bilateral cooperation here today
as part of a plan to gradually normalize relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of these six agreements is an important step in
the normalization of ties between the two states, " agreed foreign
ministers of the two countries after their meeting.
</P>
<P>
Tanjug news reports that the two ministers have signed
agreements on social insurance, legal help, border trade and
border crossings, road and railway traffic.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Foreign Minister Milan Milutinovic said he held frank
and substantial talks with his Croatian counterpart, Mate Granic,
and considerable progress has been made in improving
Yugoslav-Croatian relations.
</P>
<P>
Milutinovic said the agreements paved the way for regional
cooperation in other areas and this would also contribute to
maintaining peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Granic expressed his belief that he and Milutinovic would hold
more talks and sign other agreements on the normalization of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Granic arrived here on Monday for an official visit and talks
to speed up negotiations on economic, trade and financial
cooperation will continue on Tuesay. 
