<HEADLINE> US Praises Bosnian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
described Bosnia's municipal elections over the weekend as a step
toward peace.
</P>
<P>
"These elections are a tribute to the Bosnian people. The
grassroots elections are an important milestone along the road to
peace and reconciliation," said the White House.
</P>
<P>
"That they could proceed relatively free of disturbance is a
welcome reminder of how far Bosnia has come since the guns were
silenced barely two years ago," it said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Election organizers in Bosnia had said the two-day municipal
elections over the weekend had been conducted without serious
violence and had attracted a high voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular press briefing, State Department
spokesman James Foley said that the elections proves that the
U.S. policy of "carrots and sticks" towards Bosnia is "starting
to pay off."
</P>
<P>
He said that "tough sanctions" will be implemented in event of
non-compliance with the results of the elections held last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The threatened sanctions include denial of reconstruction aid
to municipalities that do not implement election results and
denial of travel privileges for officials who thwart the results,
added the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"We are fully determined to make full use of the tools
available to the international community to see that the aims of
Dayton (Agreement) are brought to fruition," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
