<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province's Road Building Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang
province plans to speed up road construction to make all major
cities accessible in a three-hour ride from Hangzhou, the
provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
Acting Governor Chai Songyue told a group of reporters from
Taiwan Province recently that the road-building program is open to
foreign investment in a number of ways like joint ventures,
co-operative firms, wholly-overseas owned companies, BOT
(Building-Operation-Transfer), and stock purchase.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang has been one of the fastest developing provinces in
the country. In 1996, it ranked fifth with a GDP of 415 billion
yuan, which was up from 12th in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The rapid economic development has resulted in traffic
bottlenecks, however. Since 1990, over 10 billion yuan has been
put into road-building. Over 4,000 km of highways have been built,
bringing the total figure to 34,000 km.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the Shanghai-Hangzhou-Ningbo
Expressway Joint Stock Co. Ltd. was listed on the Hong Kong Stock
Exchange and sold a third of its shares for 460 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The acting governor said that the Hong Kong listing has been a
good experience for the province in diversifying fund-raising
methods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Wharf to Ease Yangon Water Transport Congestion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A newly built wharf at Yangon
Port in Myanmar's capital will help ease water transport
congestion, said today's official paper The New Light of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The 220-meter-long wharf, which was put into service Monday,
can handle three coastal passenger vessels, five cargo boats and
four sea-going ships at one time.
</P>
<P>
The wharf is capable of handling 100,000 tons of cargo yearly
and over 80,000 passengers can be transported.
</P>
<P>
Yangon Port, Myanmar's main gateway to the world, was built
before the Second World War, and it now handles 90 percent of the
country's exports and imports.
</P>
<P>
Since Myanmar began practicing a market-oriented economy in the
late 1980s, the volume of export and import has increased sharply.
Seaborne trade passing through the ports of Myanmar was seven
million tons in the 1996-97 fiscal year ending March, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
To promote freight transport, a new 17-wharf Myanmar
international port -- Thilawa Port -- is being built near Yangon
with investments from three foreign firms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Foreign Reserves at 25.9 Bln Dollars in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's foreign exchange
reserves have dropped to 25.9 billion U.S. dollars by August 29,
the Bank of Thailand said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The figure included 1.6 billion dollars in credits recently
drawn from the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the Thai central
bank was quoted as saying by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The bank earlier announced that the country's foreign reserves
stood at 27.9 billion dollars as of August 14, which meant the
reserves could have decreased by 3.6 billion dollars if without
the IMF aid.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the decline in reserves was largely attributed to
the maturing of those currency forward contracts in late August.
</P>
<P>
The contracts were signed in mid-May this year when the central
bank moved to counter-attack speculations against the baht, they
added.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank last month said Thailand's forward
obligations totaled 23.4 billion dollars over the coming 12 months
starting on August 19, including 14.8 billion offshore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
