<HEADLINE> Outdoor Cooking Ban In Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Municipal
Government has announced a ban on outdoor stands that broil food,
in a bid to reduce air pollution and clean up the environment.
</P>
<P>
Restaurants are also prohibited from cooking outdoors to
attract more customers, and those that specialize in roasted,
fried, or broiled foods need to have a hood with a fan and an air
filter system to reduce pollution.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came last Monday from the Beijing Urban
Environment Management Office, the Municipal Administration for
Industry and Commerce, and the Beijing Municipal Health Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Outdoor food stalls have been a common sight on Beijing streets
now for many years, and most of the vendors do not have the
necessary permits and cannot guarantee the hygiene of the food or
their equipment. Some even put their stands along roads, blocking
traffic, and increasing the risk from accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
