<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Businessmen Less Optimistic About Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Filipino businessmen have
become less optimistic about the country's economic prospects due
to the financial turmoil sweeping Southeast Asia and the political
uncertainties arising from charter change movement in the country.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Business World reported today that a third
of 115 businessmen surveyed by the influential Makati Business
Club expected the gross national product (GNP) this year to be
worse compared with the impressive 6.8 percent registered last
year.
</P>
<P>
This was a sharp turnaround from the results of a survey the
club made in January, in which 78.2 percent of the businessmen
projected this year's growth rate to be higher with nobody
anticipating it to be worse than 1996.
</P>
<P>
"This reflects the least optimism in the economy dating back to
July 1994," said a statement released by the club, whose members
are mostly top executives of big enterprises in the country.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since President Fidel Ramos took power in
1992, the growth of GNP, the value of goods and services including
income from abroad, slowed down in the first half of this year to
5.9 percent from 7.5 percent in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Many blamed the slowdown on both the region-wide currency
meltdown and the political instability posed by the proposed
amendments to the 1987 Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The business community has complained that the Ramos
administration has talked too much about Charter changes instead
of the development of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos still keeps open his option whether he would
run again when his term ends next year, prompting opponents of
charter change moves to call a mass rally on September 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
