<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Andean Community to Enhance Ties With Trade Blocs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Andean Community (AC) is
looking forward to strengthening ties with other trade blocs and
integrating itself into the global trade system, said an official
of the trade bloc.
</P>
<P>
AC Secretary-General Sebastian Alegrett told the press that the
Lima-based trade bloc, which groups Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador,
Peru and Venezuela, sees it as a priority to step up free trade
negotiations with other hemispheric trading blocs and move toward
the goal of setting up a Free Trade Area of Americas (FTAA) by
2005.
</P>
<P>
"We have been loyal to the criteria of `open regionalism', so
we are looking forward to becoming related with Mercosur, the
Caribbean and Central America, to which we already have started to
approach," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Andean countries are strengthening their economy to
prepare for the creation of a free trade zone in the Western
Hemisphere, which is under negotiation.
</P>
<P>
He called for a quicker integration of the AC and the Southern
Common Market (Mercosur) which groups Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay
and Uruguay with Chile and Bolivia being its associate members.
</P>
<P>
He said that the negotiations between the AC and Mercosur on
the rules governing their free trade talks have been successful,
he said, adding that talks will resume Tuesday on tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
Alegrett said the signing of the Group of Three (G-3) Accord by
Colombia, Venezuela and Mexico was a success of the Andean
Community.
</P>
<P>
He said the AC will also move to enhance ties with the United
States and Europe on trade and cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
