<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Nuclear Power Plant to Produce Tritium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Nuclear
Regulatory Commission agreed for the first time today to allow its
Watts Bar nuclear power plant to produce tritium, a nuclear bomb
material through a commercial reactor, a move which critics say
will end its long-standing policy to bar civilian nuclear power
plants from making weapons.
</P>
<P>
The test could begin within weeks, the Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Tennessee Valley Authority (TVA) will receive 7.5 million
U.S. dollars from the Department of Energy for the Watts Bar test,
which is intended to demonstrate that a commercial light-water
reactor can produce tritium, a radioactive hydrogen isotope,
without affecting its operation.
</P>
<P>
"Our own country is saying, `North Korea doesn't produce this
tritium product'. Why are we doing it in our own country?" said
John Noel from the Tennessee Valley Energy Reform Coalition.
</P>
<P>
Ralph Hutchison of the Oak Ridge Environmental Peace Alliance
and Michelle Neal-Conlon of the Tennessee Valley Energy Reform
Coalition have sent a letter to TVA Chairman Craven Crowell
opposing the test.
</P>
<P>
"The separation of civilian and military nuclear power is a
cornerstone of U.S. international nonproliferation policy, which
will suddenly and completely vanish," they wrote.
</P>
<P>
"When the Watts Bar nuclear power plant loads tritium-producing
rods into its operating core, it becomes, to put it bluntly, a
bomb plant," they said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government shut down its heavy-water reactors at the
Savannah River site in South Carolina in 1988 and no new tritium
has been produced for weapons since then.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. Department of Energy is under a presidential
directive to find a new source for tritium by 2005 to support the
nation's nuclear arsenal, the AP report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NGO: Ukraine Becoming Europe's Dumping Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine is facing the risk of
becoming Europe's dumping ground for toxic waste due to the lack
of control over transit shipments across its territory, Yury
Samiylenko, leader of a Ukrainian environmental protection
organization warned today.
</P>
<P>
Toxic and chemical wastes have been pouring into the country
under the cover of transit shipments. He accused the Ministry for
Environmental Protection and Nuclear Safety of turning a blind eye
to such shipments.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from Samilylenko's non-governmental Ukrainian Green
Peace show that foreign wastes dumped in the country have reached
25 billion tons, of which more than 4 billion tons are categorized
as toxic. If divided by the area of Ukraine, this will make up
40,000 tons of foreign rubbish per square meter.
</P>
<P>
Samiylenko said that nobody wants to clean up the waste inside
the Ukrainian borders and no one is investigating the source of
the waste.
</P>
<P>
He also cast doubt over the behavior of Ukrainian customs
officials, saying that "Customs officials are experienced in
seizing smuggled alcohol and tobacco, but why should they give the
green light to foreign garbage?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
