<HEADLINE> Travel Popular Among Shanghai Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Xu Weijun, a college
graduate who works as a bank clerk, often spends weekends
and public holidays travelling, and explains, "Working with
statistics every day is so dull. Travel helps me relax."
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of Shanghai's citizens are doing like Miss
Xu and taking some time out of their busy schedules to travel.
</P>
<P>
Travel has become a fad. In 1996, on average Shanghai families
spent 527 yuan (63 US dollars) on travel and entertainment, 2.6
times the 1992 figure.
</P>
<P>
Local travel agencies say that more Shanghai people are
travelling by themselves rather than joining a tour group. More of
them are going longer distances, travelling by air, and their
food, lodging, and transport expectations are rising as well.
</P>
<P>
While the classic sights of nearby Jiangsu and Zhejiang
provinces, like the cities of Suzhou, Shaoxing, and Ningbo, have
always been popular with Shanghai residents, a growing number of
people are going farther away to places like Hainan Island, Mohe
in northernmost Heilongjiang Province, or to Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Tours to Southeast Asia, Hongkong, and Macao have also become a
favored choice of people who are better-off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
