<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists working on Stronger Hepatitis B Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese scientists
are trying to develop a more powerful vaccine to control hepatitis
B in China, where roughly one in ten people carry the virus,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The China National Biological Products Corp (CNBPC) attached to
the Ministry of Health, in co-operation with Shanghai Medical
University and foreign research centers, has already begun
researching into the new vaccine, said Jiang Huanbo, president of
the CNBPC.
</P>
<P>
He said their research is well underway, and he hoped for a
breakthrough in hepatitis B control in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Data from the Ministry of Health suggest that about ten percent
of the Chinese population carry hepatitis B virus, which is
transmitted through infected blood.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health began hepatitis B vaccine research in the
late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Through expanded immunization, about 90 percent of urban
children are given hepatitis B vaccination immediately after
birth. The program has reduced the incidence rate of hepatitis B to
below one percent among children in urban areas. The immunization
rate among rural children has also increased.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 enterprises and institutions manufacture some 200
varieties of bio-pharmaceuticals in China, Jiang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
