<HEADLINE> Latin America Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
major economic briefs in Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina`s economy is expected to grow 5.8
percent and the public deficit might decrease from 4.5 billion
this year to 3.4 billion dollars in 1998, said Roque Fernandez,
the minister of economy and public works.
</P>
<P>
According to a budgetary report Fernandez will submit to
Congress, trade deficit in 1998 will be 5.3 billion dollars, while
investments will continue to be the main factor for economic
growth in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
He added that the inflation rate will post a 1.8 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua's largest sugar mill, San Antonio
Chichilapa sugar mill, may lose more than 5 million U.S. dollars
this season due to the climatic phenomenon of "El Nino", said the
sugar company's vice manager, Joaquin Zavala.
</P>
<P>
Its output for 1997-98 harvest time is expected to reach 4
million quintals of sugar, he said. Due to damage caused by
droughts, the mill may suffer a loss of 10 percent of the expected
output, he added.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil`s state-owned oil company Petrobras
announced it will issue a package of bonds worth 350 million
U.S. dollars overseas.
</P>
<P>
Out of that amount, 200 million dollars will be sold to the
United States and 150 million dollars to Europe, Finance Director
of Petrobras, Orlando Galvao said.
</P>
<P>
This would be the third time for Petrobras to issue bonds
overseas to earn foreign currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
