<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, September 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Monday rejected recent allegations by the
United States that Iran is the main source of tension in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"First of all Iran is not the source of tension in the Middle
East; the presence of foreign forces and the U.S. in the region is
the source of tension," Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi
said, responding to a question posed by Xinhua, at his first press
conference since taking office on August 20.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright reportedly said last
week when she was visiting Israel that Iran is the source of
tension in the Middle East. (Iran-US-Relations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The French government will open seven head digits of
phone numbers for lots drawing Monday evening in a symbolic move
to break state monopoly in the country's telecommunication market.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the state-owned France Telecom, Cegetal.
telecommunication group, Bouygues of the Italian telecommunication
group STET, and Siris, owned by the European consortium Unisource
and the U.S. giant AT&AMP;T, are competitors for the digits.
(France-Telecommunication)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain and Ireland issued a joint statement today to
persuade pro-British unionists into joining the Northern Ireland
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The statement, by Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain and
Bertie Ahern of Ireland, was made in Belfast, of Northern Ireland,
just before the negotiations were due to open.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the two main concerns of the Ulster Unionist Party
(UUP), the two leaders pledged that the people of Northern Ireland
would decide the territory's future and that they wanted
guerrillas to disarm during the talks. (Britain-Ireland-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Razali Ismail, President of the 51st General
Assembly of the United Nations, Monday called on member states to
unite and make real efforts for the on-going reforms and
strengthening of the world body.
</P>
<P>
In a closing address, Razali said that U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's reform package put forward in mid-July "deserves our
full and expeditious attention without being casualty to
politics."
</P>
<P>
"The task of strengthening the UN will depend in large part on
the UN's ability to adapt to change, beyond creeping incremental
adjustments," he noted. (UN-Reforms)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU -- The abduction of Idiris Mohamed Osman, an aid
worker from the World Food Program (WFP) in the Somali capital
ended peacefully Sunday night after the intervention of community
elders and officials from WFP.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Salah Garad Omar, a Somali official from the WFP who
was flown from Nairobi for the release efforts, said with the help
of the elders, the abduction of Osman ended without the payment of
any kind of ransom.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about those who kidnapped Osman, Garad blamed
militiamen loyal to the local non-governmental organization (NGO),
Green Hope, for being behind the abduction. (Somalia-Abductee
Released)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq has decided to allow 93 Iranian citizens living
in the United States to come to visit Shiite Muslim holy shrines
in Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Tourism Authority has authorized the granting of
entry visas to 93 Iranian passport holders, INA said.
</P>
<P>
They are the first batch of overseas Iranians permitted to
enter Iraq for pilgrimage under an instruction by Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein. (Iraq-Iran-Pilgrimage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Aircraft debris have been found some 250 kilometers off
the Namibian coast two days after a German and a U.S. military
planes went missing in the area over the South Atlantic, reports
reaching here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
German media quoted Namibian air traffic control authorities as
saying on Monday that a Namibian ship had spotted about 20 pieces
of debris, including half a aircraft seat, a piece of a cabin door
and German papers, 255 kilometers northwest of Walvis Bay in
Namibia. (Germany-US-Planes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States grounded its stealth fighters
Monday after one of the craft crashed during an air show in
Maryland Sunday and investigations started on the losses of three
military aircraft over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
An Air Force F-117A "Nighthawk" crashed on the skirts of
Baltimore Sunday; a Navy F-A-18 Hornet crashed in Oman and its
pilot was killed; and an Air Force C-141 transport is presumed
lost after a potential mid-air collision with a German military
plane off the coast of Africa. (US-Stealth-Fighters)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The Swiss Federal Council (government) said Monday
that the suspension of a Swiss special fund caused by the absence
of three Jewish members was a "deplorable" incident.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Swiss government praised members from the
World Jewish Restitution Organization and asked them to have their
suggestions ready by December 25 to resume the work of the special
fund for holocaust victims and their families.
(Switzerland-Fund-Jews)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien said Monday
that he has enough on his plate and doesn't want to be dragged
into the monarchy debate now.
</P>
<P>
Chretien has been asked to clarify his stand on the issue
whether the country should cut its ties with the British monarchy.
</P>
<P>
"I have enough with the separatists of Quebec. I don't want to
have problems with the monarchists of Canada at this time," he
told reporters. (Canada-PM-Monarchy) 
</P>
