<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senna Trial to Re-start in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The trial over the death of
Brazilian Aryton Senna will be reopened in Imola, Italy on
Tuesday, with six men facing manslaughter charges.
</P>
<P>
The accused were team owner Frank Williams, technical director
Patrick Head and chief designer Adrian Newey, along with three
race officials at the 1994 San Marino race.
</P>
<P>
State prosecutor Maurizio Passarini said that Senna's modified
steering column failed as the triple world champion took the
Tamburello curve which smashed his car into a concrete wall at
high speed.
</P>
<P>
Passarini was to recall former Italian Formula One driver
Michele Alboreto to the witness box.
</P>
<P>
In a previous court appearace, Alboreto said he had not noticed
Senna making any particular correcting movements of the wheel,
which might indicate a steering column failure.
</P>
<P>
However, Passarini has since reportedly shown Alboreto a
better-defined tape of the same images, supplied by the sport's
ruling International Automobile Federation (FIA).
</P>
<P>
After watching these pictures, Alboreto was believed to have
revised his opinion and noticed Senna make a clearer sideways
movement at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
All six denied the charges which have a maximum sentence of
five years, the first ever to be levelled against a Formula One
team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pele Proposes Cleaning Up Sports in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Former world soccer star
Pele, now sports minister of Brazil, presented his contraversial
bill to Brazil's Congress on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bill aimed at cleaning up the Brazilian domestic soccer and
was facing a long and uncertain journey through Congress.
</P>
<P>
Pele's proposals have angered FIFA's Brazilian president Joao
Havelange. Havelange warned in August that if the bill was
approved Brazil would run the risk of being expelled from next
year's World Cup in France.
</P>
<P>
Pele's proposals were to reduce the power of the Brazilian
Football Confeferation (CBF) and to turn soccer clubs into private
firms subject to strict financial laws.
</P>
<P>
The law would also tighten up refereeing, bypassing the CBF
which has been widely criticised for its handling of an alleged
referee-buying scandal earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
"The whole of Brazilian society is ashamed of what is going on
in sport, especially in soccer," said Pele. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
