<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana, Spain Enter Semis at Under-17 World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Reigning champion Ghana nipped
Oman 4-1 and Spain routed Egypt 2-1 on Monday, both securing their
semifinal berths at the seventh Under-17 World Championship in
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Played in the Mediterranean city of Port Said, twice champion
Ghana displayed its superiority in physique and tactical skills
over Oman, the African fourth-ranked team in the previous U-17
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
The first half saw Ghana achieve a 2-0 advantage, including an
own goal from Omani Mahfoudh Sabir Al Mukhaini who scored his own
net in the 24th minute when he tried to clear a shot amid a
tangled fight.
</P>
<P>
In the 41st minute, Michael Coffie scored the second for Ghana
from a pass above the top of the penalty box, catching the Omani
goalie lying on the ground too late to save.
</P>
<P>
Oman fought back to score in the 57th minute with a clever
header by Salah Al-Amari.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Ghana's attacks showed no sign of recess and finally
sealed the game 4-1 with two more powerful kicks by Afriyie Owusu
and Quaye Awule in the 79th and 88th minutes.
</P>
<P>
With the win, Ghana sailed to the semifinals to meet Spain that
defeated Egypt in the fourth quarterfinal match played in the Suez
Canal city of Ismailia.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian eleven seemed determined to tread their line
cautiously at the outset while Spain, the 1991 U-17 World Cup
runner-up, concentrated more on avoiding rash moves.
</P>
<P>
In the 27th minute, Spain opened the account with a furious
start from the left which resulted in a clean kick into the net
before the Egyptians could hardly hurry up for their defense.
</P>
<P>
The hosts stepped up their tempo of offense and equalized three
minutes later as Ahmed Belel and Mohamed Abou el-Ela converted a
well-crafted pass into a powerful shot.
</P>
<P>
The second half saw more fierce attacks on both sides until
Juan Camacho scored the winner for Spain in the 65th minute.
Afterwards, the Egyptians were almost to make even but a kick hit
the post and rebounded out.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was thus kicked out of the championship that started on
September 4.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, runner-up at the U-17 World Cup, will play Germany in
Ismailia in the first semifinal on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
