<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Booming Xinjiang Border Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Border Trade Market in
Horgos, a border town in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, is filled with business people and shoppers
bargaining in the Chinese, Uygur, Russian and Kazak languages.
</P>
<P>
Merchants from Russia and a number of Central Asian nations
fill bags, some of which are two meters long, with Chinese
cosmetics, clothing and other daily-use items.
</P>
<P>
The aforementioned scenarios are a daily occurrence in the
market which is located in close proximity with the border of
Kazakstan. Ten years ago, Horgos was heavily fortified with
armed soldiers closely monitoring their counterpart's movements on
the other side of the borders.
</P>
<P>
The Horgos market, which covers 120,000 sq m and was built at a
cost of 70 million yuan, is only one of a dozen border markets
which have emerged along Xinjiang's 5,000 km of border with seven
Central Asian countries, Mongolia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the central government decided to open Yining, Tacheng
and Bole, as well as the regional capital city of Urumqi to
foreign traders, and later opened 12 border ports of entry,
including Horgos, Alataw and Paketu.
</P>
<P>
Border trade, which was nonexistant for decades due to
political reasons, has witnessed a new upsurge.
</P>
<P>
The markets have attracted numerous business people from
China's inland and coastal areas, as well as from neighboring
countries. Some 15,000 traders from the Commonwealth of
Independent States visited the Horgos market in the the first five
months this year alone.
</P>
<P>
One Kazak woman said she was unable to remember how many times
she had visited the market. She pointed to a bag filled with
children's shoes and said: "I can sell them for 1,000 US dollars
in just one week and earn 1,000 dollars."
</P>
<P>
Booming border trade has provided greatly increased local
revenues for Xinjiang's border areas which cover 10 prefectures and
33 counties and cities.
</P>
<P>
Official sources report that Xinjiang handled border trade
totaling 700 million US dollars in 1996 alone. Many local people
achieved prosperity from their participation in border trade and
related businesses.
</P>
<P>
The highway transport business has also flourished in
the area, with over 20 cargo and passenger transport routes
currently linking Xinjiang border towns with neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
Local economists note that the business corridor along the
border area is expected to become one of the most active market
belts in the world by early next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
