school years was launched by the Australian government yesterday,
shackling 420 million U.S. dollars in national grants to the
states to the reduction of illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Australia will urgently send a team of experts to Papua New
Guinea to assess the plight of drought-stricken villagers in the
Highlands and other areas, and how best to help them. About
700,000 people in the country are reportedly suffering from a
widespread drought, part of worldwide El Nino effects.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Leaders from Pacific island states threatened by rising
ocean levels are warning Australia's strong opposition to binding
gas emission reduction levels could provoke regional protests as
strong as those against France over its nuclear testing. The
leaders are meeting ahead of Australian Prime Minister John
Howard's arrival in the Cook Islands tomorrow for an annual
regional forum.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- A surge in tax revenue from strong wages growth will give
the Australian federal government a 2.8 billion U.S. dollar budget
"war chest" to help sell its tax-reform package in the lead-up to
the next election late next year. 
