<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cash Offer to HK Medalists at National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Medal winners of the Hong
Kong team at the forthcoming Eighth National Games of China will
be awarded cash incentives, it was learned here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The incentives are offered by the Sports Aid Committee of the
Hong Kong Sports Development Board (SDB) and matched by
locally-incorporated Hang Seng Bank on a dollar-for-dollar basis.
</P>
<P>
An individual event gold medalist of the games will be able to
walk away with a hefty sum of 300,000 HK dollars (38,462
U.S. dollars), while silver medal and bronze medal winners will
collect 150,000 HK dollars (19,230 U.S. dollars) and 60,000 HK
dollars (7,692 U.S. dollars) respectively, according to Andrew Ma,
SDB chief executive.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed cash awards for a gold medal winning team
which will pocket 420,000 HK dollars (53,846 U.S. dollars). A sum
of 240,000 HK dollars (30,769 U.S. dollars) will be offered to a
team silver medal and 120,000 HK dollars (15,385 U.S. dollars) to
a team bronze.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time Hang Seng Bank joins the SDB in
offering cash incentives to outstanding Hong Kong athletes at
major games, said Ma. The bank had contributed more than 1 million
HK dollars (128,205 U.S. dollars) through the 1996 Olympics and
Paralympics Incentive Scheme.
</P>
<P>
The cash incentives, first introduced by the SDB in 1994 for
the Asian Games, have since been extended to cover the Olympics,
Paralympics, East Asian Games and World Universiade.
</P>
<P>
The National Games will be the sixth major games where cash
incentives are on offer.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the National Games for the first time, the
post-handover Hong Kong will be represented by a contingent of
262, including 169 athletes taking part in 20 sports.
</P>
<P>
The National Games, to be held in Shanghai, will feature more
than 13,000 athletes from 46 teams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
