<HEADLINE> Germany Can Make Grade for Joining Euro: Ifo Institute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A leading German economic
institute today said that it saw increasing chances for Germany to
cut its 1997 budget deficit to 3 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) to make the grade for joining the planned single
European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
In its latest economic report released today, the Munich-based
Ifo institute revised its projections of the 1997 German budget
deficit from 3.3 percent of GDP estimated earlier to 3.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
It said that the latest projection was based on the latest
economic figures released by the German Federal Statistics Office,
according to which Germany had managed to bring down its budget
deficit from 3.5 percent of GDP in 1996 to 3.1 percent for the
first half of this year and had achieved an economic growth of 2.0
percent during the same period.
</P>
<P>
In order to make sure its place in the Euro club, Germany
should spur further economic upswing, increase tax revenues in the
second half of 1997 and maintain its budget consolidation efforts,
the Ifo said.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the Ifo institute today also publicized a survey
participated by about 450 economic experts worldwide showing that
the international economic climate had been improving in general.
</P>
<P>
While the German and Japanese economies were heating up a
little bit, the U.S. and British economies would probably expect a
slight weakening, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
The Ifo survey also predicted that the U.S. dollar would remain
strong in the next six months, profiting from the widespread
uncertainty over the stability of the planned common European
currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
