<HEADLINE> Parti Quebecois to Push for Sovereignty: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Parti Quebecois
should focus more on separation now that the other nine provinces
failed to recognize Quebec's uniqueness, a top Quebec official
said today.
</P>
<P>
The unity proposal from the premiers' unity meeting doesn't
offer Quebec any new powers to protect its language or culture,
said Jacques Brassard, Quebec minister of intergovernmental
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Nine of Canada's provincial leaders agreed at their Calgary
meeting to hold consultations on the recognition of Quebec's
"unique character" and stressed the principle of equality of all
Canadians.
</P>
<P>
"It's a step backwards," Brassard said, adding that the meeting
offers less than the failed Meech Lake and Charlottetown
constitutional accords.
</P>
<P>
"I think the sovereignty movement has to get back into gear
again," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The consultations, which will be likely to start this fall and
finish by Christmas, are designed as a goodwill gesture to Quebec
from the English-speaking provinces.
</P>
<P>
They are also aimed at helping Daniel Johnson, leader of
Quebec's Liberal Party, who will face off against Premier Lucien
Bouchard, leader of the separatist Parti Quebecois. 
</P>
</TEXT>
