<HEADLINE> (Updated) Weld Gives Up Fight for US Ambassadorship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton today agreed to accept the withdrawal of William Weld, his
nominee for ambassador to Mexico, from the nomination.
</P>
<P>
Weld, the moderate Republican nominated by Clinton to be U.S.
ambassador to Mexico in July, announced today that he abandoned
his fight for the post after conservative Sen. Jesse Helms refused
to hold a confirmation hearing on his nomination.
</P>
<P>
At a White House news conference, Weld said, "I asked President
Clinton to withdraw my name... so I can go back to New England,
where no one has to approach the government on bended knee to ask
it to do its duty."
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Clinton said he accepted Weld's decision with
"great disappointment."
</P>
<P>
"The American people have not been well served in this
process.... The treatment my nominee received reflects a
divisiveness that does not serve the American people," Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Michael McCurry said that a new nominee
would not be named soon. The selection process "is back at the
starting point now."
</P>
<P>
Weld, who resigned from the governorship of Massachusetts last
month, said he would have been nominated if a confirmation hearing
had not been blocked by Helms, the conservative North Carolina
senator he derisively called "that man."
</P>
<P>
Helms, who chairs the Senate Foreign Relations Committee,
refused to reconsider the nomination at a special meeting of the
committee last week.
</P>
<P>
The nomination needs to be first approved before it goes to
a full Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
Weld praised Clinton for fighting on his behalf. "The president
has stood tree-tops tall on this entire matter," Weld said.
</P>
<P>
Weld called Washington "a funny town" and accused Helms of
criticizing him "as though shot from guns." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
