<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Welcomes Efforts To Elimination of Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today welcomed the efforts towards elimination of
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
In a massage to the International Conference on "Central Asia
-- Nuclear-Weapon-Free Zone," being held in Tashkent, Uzbekistan,
from September 14 to 16, Annan said, "The idea of establishing
nuclear-weapon-free zones around the world had gained momentum.
The principle of denuclearization had been applied successfully in
Latin America and Caribbean, where earlier this year the Treaty of
Tlatelolco celebrated its 30th anniversary; in the South Pacific,
with the Treaty of Rarotongo; in South-east Asia, with the treaty
of Bangkok; and with the Treaty of Pelindaba covering all of
Africa."
</P>
<P>
"More than 100 United Nations member states are parties to
these agreements. With Antarctica included, they form a
nuclear-weapon-free mantle over a vast, densely populated area of
the southern hemisphere," said the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
"The elimination of nuclear weapons, a goal shared by all
humanity, is a feasible long-rang objective. The Treaty on the
Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT) represents the single
most important effort of the international community in this
direction. The indefinite extension of the NPT, and last year's
adoption by the United Nations General Assembly of the
comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty, have strengthened
considerably the nuclear non-proliferation regime," said the
secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
"Still, uncertainties and serious challenges remain, in both
the nuclear and conventional fields, and a new international
security agenda must be agreed that take account of our rapidly
changing world," Annan added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
