<DOCNO> XIE19970916.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Shifting Position on Landmines Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States, making
a reversal in its stand on landmines, agreed today to sign a
global treaty banning anti-personnel landmines, but on conditions,
including the use of the weapon on the Korean Peninsula for nine
years.
</P>
<P>
"We have come forward with a compromise proposal, which is
being discussed now among a number of delegations in Oslo," State
Department spokesman James Foley told reporters at a regular
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"The United States decided that we could drop our proposed
exception for Korea and we would resolve our security concerns, in
Korea and elsewhere, through a time-bound deferral period long
enough to meet our needs: nine years, that is," he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States at first was intent on boycotting the Oslo
conference on anti-personnel landmines. But it later decided to
attend the meeting in an attempt to push for an exemption for the
Korean Peninsula for the use of the weapon.
</P>
<P>
One U.S. official said the nine-year phase-in period "would
give us, in the estimation of the military and others, an adequate
opportunity to develop alternatives" to anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
Another official said the "deferral period" would permit the
United States to deploy self-destructing "smart" anti-personnel
mines that are positioned near anti-tank mines.
</P>
<P>
Foley said the United States was also seeking "two absolutely
critical modifications in the current draft text of the treaty"
banning the anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
The first is a "reversion... on treaty withdrawal."
</P>
<P>
"We would need to include a clause (in the draft text), a
clause that would allow countries to withdraw from the treaty if
they or their allies are victims of aggression," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
He noted the current treaty text "does not allow signers to
withdraw during a conflict, while other arms control treaties,
such as the Chemical Weapons Treaty, do not restrict the right to
withdraw."
</P>
<P>
The second is "to revise the current draft text definition of
anti-handling devices, to avoid banning U.S. anti-tank munitions,"
Foley said.
</P>
<P>
Republican Senator Patrick Leahy, who had led the fight in
Congress for a global ban on landmines, said the concession that
the Clinton administration had made was not enough.
</P>
<P>
"This looks like the same old exceptions wrapped in new
packaging," he said. "To get to the finish line, U.S. negotiators
are going to need more than cosmetic changes in our position. They
will require fresh thinking, and time is running out."
</P>
<P>
Jody Williams, who is attending the Oslo conference on behalf
of the international campaign to ban landmines, also was critical
of the U.S. conditions for its signing of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
"If successful, this last-ditch effort by the U.S. would gut
the treaty," he said. "It would be a document fatally flawed by
a... gaping loophole and a lengthy, deadly delay." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
